<HEADLINE> More Palestinians Rioting in Hebron, Nablus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian rioters continued
clashing with Israeli soldiers in West Bank city Hebron today,
while thousands of others staged an anti-Israel and
anti-U.S. demonstration in Nablus.
</P>
<P>
At least 20 Palestinian protesters were injured in Hebron
by Israeli soldiers, who fired rubber bullets and gas grenades
from balconies and roof-tops to disperse them. No Israeli
casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the eighth straight today that the violent
confrontation continued in Hebron. More than 100 Palestinians have
been injured in the latest wave of violence, which was sparked by
the United States congress' vote on moving the U.S. Embassy from
Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several thousands of angry Palestinians held an
anti-Israel and anti-U.S. demonstration in another West Bank city
of Hebron. Protesters chanted anti-Israel and anti-U.S. slogans
and burned Israeli and U.S. flags to protest the U.S. support to
Israel's claim on the disputed holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators also intended to march to the Jewish holy
site of the Joseph's Tomb guarded by Israeli soldiers, but they
were blocked by Palestinian police deployed to prevent violent
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
During the Israeli-Palestinian bloodshed last September sparked
by Israel's opening of the underground archaeological tunnel in
East Jerusalem, the Joseph's tomb was the scene of the bloodiest
clash where six Israeli soldiers were killed by Palestinian
protesters and policemen.
</P>
<P>
The continued violence in Hebron and the demonstration in
Nablus highlights the rising tension between the two sides due to
the prolonged deadlock in the peace talks, which were frozen since
March when Israel began building the controversial Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
