<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Rocket Guerrilla Base in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes carried out at
noon today an air raid at a suspected guerrilla base in south
Lebanon, in an apparent retaliation for an attack on Isaeli
occupation forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that the Israeli warplanes launched the
strike at 12:15 a.m. (0945 GMT) in Iglim Al-Toffah, a ridge
some 65 kilometers southeast of Beirut which is often used
by Muslim guerrillas as a springboard to attack the Israeli
self-carved buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli fighter-bombers fired two air-to-surfaces missiles
on the hill of Tellat Mlita in the area, the security sources
added, noting that no casualties were caused.
</P>
<P>
The air raid followed, and was followed by artillery
bombardments at the heights and reconnaissance flights of Israeli
warplanes over the area.
</P>
<P>
Radio of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia
comfirmed that the Israeli position of Bir Kalab deeply inside the
border strip was attacked by guerrillas, but denied any casualties.
</P>
<P>
In another development, six Irish soldiers of the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), which is engaged in a peacekeeping
mission in south Lebanon, were wounded this morning as a result of
a mine explosion in the area of Beit Yahoun.
</P>
<P>
The six have been sent to a field hospital of the
multi-national forces in the south Lebanese border town of
Naqoura and UNIFIl's spokesman Timor Goksel said that two Irish
soldiers were in serious state when four others were slightly
injured.
</P>
<P>
Goksel said that the soldiers were wounded when patrolling a
road in Beit Yahoun inside the Israeli-occupied enclave "after the
UNIFIL was informed by the Israeli side that the road was free of
mines."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force, comprising contingents from Fiji, Finland,
France, Ghana, Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and Poland, was set
up in 1978 following the first Israeli incursion into the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the UNIFIL's installation, some 200 peacekeepers have
died and more others wounded in various incidents on the last
active battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
