<HEADLINE> McRae Leads First Day of China Auto Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Colin McRae of Britain led the
China Auto Rally competition after the first day's eight stages
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
McRae, the 1995 world champion, clocked one hour, 37 minutes
and 58 seconds, followed by Swede Kenneth Eriksson in second place
39 second behind. Japan's Yoshio Fujimoto was third at 1:42:24.
</P>
<P>
The weather was hot and dry in most parts of the stages but
some sections of the road was slippery on some corners.
</P>
<P>
McRae almost rolled over his car on a big jump amid the opening
special stage.
</P>
<P>
"If I had been on full attack that would have been a major
moment," said McRae. "We had that bump in our notes as a caution
and luckily we had slowed down."
</P>
<P>
Ten Chinese drivers took part in the rally, with Lu Ningjun
having the best placing at eighth.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Yong, who drove a N-class car for the first time, placed
ninth.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two cars entered the competition at the start of the day
but 13 of them was forced out due to various reasons.
</P>
<P>
The surviving 19 cars will race through Sunday's eight stages
which total 143.03 kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
