<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Calls for European Cooperation in Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
today called for closer cooperation among European countries to
enhance the competitiveness of Europe's airspace industry in the
face of fierce competition from American airspace groups.
</P>
<P>
"Any future program, whether civilian or military, cannot from
now on avoid the imperative of (European) cooperation," said
Jospin when visiting the Paris Air Show at Bourget.
</P>
<P>
He said that only when all the European countries put together
their efforts to develop the continent's airspace industry, can
they maintain an equal stand with the United States in the field.
</P>
<P>
While praising the dynamism in civilian airspace programs such
as the Airbus series passenger planes, Jospin said that Europe is
experiencing a difficult period in its military airspace industry.
</P>
<P>
"The necessary amalgamation of defense industries remains an
object of study without being started. We should start rapidly but
with method which, in this essential field for our sovereignty,
cannot be done without the participation of the state. The
government will play fully its role which has returned to the
field," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jospin also said that the government will continue to reduce
spending in buying armaments under an overall control of public
spending.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the U.S. government for protectionism in American
airspace market and called for a "balanced and transparent"
competition between European and American airspace industries.
</P>
<P>
"The recent appearance of the unusual commercial practices on
the American market -- I think notably to about the exclusive
contracts signed by Boeing for very long distance planes with
three biggest American companies -- is very worrying,"said Jospin.
</P>
</TEXT>
