<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges G-7, Russia to Work for Common Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today urged leaders of the Group of Seven industrialized countries and
Russia to work together to meet global challenges.
</P>
<P>
Opening the first working session of the three-day Denver Summit of
the Eight, Clinton said no one can meet challenges such as currency
crisis, organized crime or infectious diseases
</P>
<P>
"Our challenge in this moment of peace and stability is to
organize ourselves for the future; to make change work fo us, not
against us," Clinton told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which opened on Friday night, was attended by British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien,
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi, French President Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Also Russian President Boris Yeltsin attended the whole process
of the event for the first time since Moscow was invited to
participate the discussions in 1991.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda of the summit are macro-economic policies,
economic globalization, social and political issues in the current
world.
</P>
<P>
"We must seize the opportunities of the global economy to expand
our own prosperity, bring in other nations that want to share in its
benefits, and work together to meet the new threats,"Clinton told
the leaders.
</P>
<P>
"None of our nations can meet these challenges alone, and more
than ever our summit process is an engine of common progress," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are to discuss "the best ways to deepen and extend the
benefits of the 21st century marketplace, to help our societies
thrive as our population grow older, to strengthen further the
stability of the world financial system, to generate economic growth
throughout the world," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
As a host of the summit, the U.S. seeks support from the eight
countries for its initiatives in several areas, including a plan to
help Africa develop economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leaders will also discuss cooperation to meet
threats such as nuclear smuggling, international crimes and
infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
The summit took place at the Denver Public Library in downtown.
"It is fitting that we meet in a public library, a place where
people come together to learn and share ideas without regard to
their own backgrounds," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
