<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Invites Saddam to OIC Summit in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today officially invited his Iraqi counterpart Saddam
Hussein to Tehran for the 8th Summit of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) due to be held in December.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the invitation
was delivered by Iranian Health and Medical Education Minister
Ali Reza Marandi in his meeting with Saddam in Baghdad today.
</P>
<P>
It said that Saddam told the Iranian envoy that his government
was ready to improve relations with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
In response, Marandi voiced the commitment of the Iranian
government to solve existing problems between Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed Iran's concern for the territorial integrity
of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Saddam did not say whether he would go to Tehran for
the OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
A senior Iraqi diplomat told Xinhua recently that Saddam
would not come here for the forthcoming OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
Salah N. Al-Samarmad, Charge d'affaires of the Iraqi embassy,
said that the Iraqi president would not come to Tehran despite
Rafsanjani's invitation.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, one of Iraq's vice-presidents would come to
Tehran to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
Al-Samarmad admitted that both Iraq and Iran have the
intention to improve their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Marandi, who arrived in Baghdad Thursday, is the first Iranian
high-ranking official visiting Iraq in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought a bloody war from 1980 to 1988. So, it
is not easy for the two countries to untie the knot, observers
here noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
