<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Endorses Government's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti National Assembly
today endorsed the government policy of reconciling relations
with the Arab countries which supported Iraq during the Gulf War
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that the parliament during a closed-door
session today ended a week-long deliberation on the government's
foreign policy, especially towards those Arab countries whose
"ties with Kuwait were strained after siding with the Iraqi regime
during its invasion of Kuwait in 1990."
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary members expressed their desire to cooperate
with the government on the initiative.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti first deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber voiced pleasure on the
parliament's positive response to the foreign strategy on keeping
Kuwait close to the Arab arena.
</P>
<P>
He said "the assembly agreed that Kuwait should not be
isolated" from the Arab community.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government started earlier this year an initiative
to reconcile relations with Arab countries, namely Jordan, Sudan
and Yemen, which it regarded as pro-Iraq during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Sabah recently announced that Kuwait would restore its
relations with some of the countries that supported the Iraqi
regime, but he did set a date for the restoration of relations.
</P>
<P>
Local Arabic daily Al-Watan today quoted a Kuwaiti high-ranking
source as saying Kuwait's ties with Jordan and Yemen would resume
in two months.
</P>
<P>
The source said the "upcoming few weeks will witness
practical steps towards the resumption of relations with Jordan"
adding that Kuwait would appoint two ambassadors in Amman and
Sanna "during the next two months."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Kuwait Airways Corporation and Jordanian Royal
Airlines would re-operate their flights between Kuwait and Amman
next July.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Abudel Salam Al-Majali said Friday
that the atmosphere between Kuwait and Jordan was clearing up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
