<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-21 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM: Egypt Peace Drive Unbaffled by Threat of Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will go on with its efforts
to salvage the peace process and put it back on track despite the
obstruction from the U.S. Congress, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said today.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will continue its peace drive according to the Madrid
conference terms of reference, the land-for-peace principle and
the timetable included in the Oslo agreement, Moussa told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"There are many obstacles in this respect but Egypt will not
be disheartened," he said, commenting on the foreign aid package
approved Wednesday by the U.S. Senate Appropriations subcommittee
that sets aside no money for Cairo.
</P>
<P>
If the bill is enacted, for the first time since Egypt and
Israel signed the U.S.-brokered Camp David peace accords of 1978,
of the two signatories, only Israel would be assured of a
multi-billion-dollar share in the annual U.S. foreign aid budget.
</P>
<P>
Washington also announced last week that it was creating a
Middle East peace and stability fund that would raise 100 million
U.S. dollars of aid to Jordan and possibly other countries
actively involved in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. attempts to use the aid as a pressure card
on Egypt, Moussa said that the Clinton administration's position
toward the Egyptian peace role is clear that "it should not be
disturbed."
</P>
<P>
After the subcommittee decision, the U.S. State Department
Thursday insisted on its request for more than 2 billion dollars
in aid specially targeted for Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years and especially since 1978, Egypt has
received more than 20 billion in U.S. aid, second only to
Israel in the amount of U.S. aid to any single country.
</P>
<P>
On the Egyptian coordination with Israel, the foreign minister
said the Egyptian mediation efforts were going in the same line
and both sides were still in contact.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Friday exchanged views with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu on a fresh initiative
aimed at unlocking the logjam in the peace process, which stalled
in March when Israel broke ground for a new Jewish settlement in
disputed East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But the top Egyptian diplomat denied the existence of any new
initiative, saying that the Palestinians and Israelis are
negotiating on the initiatives and ideas previously launched by
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also stressed the impact of the Egyptian-European
contacts held over the past three days on activating the peace
process and the role of 15 European countries "linked to the
Mideast region with different ties."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's European tour launched to get the peace process off
hook, has taken him to France and Germany since Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
