<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia on Close Watch of Bombing Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia watches closely
the new developments in the case of last June's bombing of a
U.S. servicemen compound in the Kingdom, Saudi deputy Interior
Minister prince Ahmad Ben Abdel Aziz said today
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the expatriation of Saudi national Hani
Al-Sayegh from Canada to the United States for alleged involvement
in the Al-Khobar truck bombing last June that killed 19
U.S. airmen.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating an Arab anti-drug conference in Jeddah, a Saudi
red-sea coast city, Ahmad said Saudi Arabia considered the case as
of special importance to it, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sayegh was detained several months ago in Canada after
authorities there refused to grant him political asylum and
considered him a terrorist and a threat to Canadian security.
</P>
<P>
Canadian court documents accused him of having been a driver of
a car that gave the go-ahead signal for the bomb-laden truck
involved in the bombing attack and of being a member of the
radical Saudi Hezbollah. But he has maintained his innocence of
involvement with the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Canadian authorities ruled last month he should be deported as
a suspected terrorist, so Sayegh was extradited to the U.S. last
week and would be tried in the U.S. next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sayegh denied taking part in the bombing and said he was in
Iran at the time when the bombing took place. But he confessed to
taking part in another abortive attempt against U.S. nationals in
Saudi Arabia in December 1995. 
</P>
