<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Lifts Ban on Restaurants, Food Vendors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government
today lifted a ban on restaurants and food vendors imposed early
this month to check further spread of cholera.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at his office in the town of
Zanzibar, the Isles Minister for Health, Said Bakari Jecha, said
the decision to allow restaurants and food vendors to do their
business effective from tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
He said the unbanning will be followed by the stringent health
check ups by health officers to ensure that all hygienic rules
were met. The use of plastic utensils are still banned, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied that we have been able to certain extent
control the killer disease," explained the minister, adding that
unlike in the past, few cholera cases are now reported.
</P>
<P>
Jecha further said that a ban on the importation of fruits and
vegetables from the Mainland was still there to stay.
</P>
<P>
But he said some few clean tourist hotels would be licenced to
import vegetation and fruits from the Mainland.
</P>
<P>
Since the closure of restaurants to check the spread of the
epidemic, which has so far killed more than 40 people and
affected 260 others, the government has been under criticism for
failing to inspect each restaurant before imposing the decision.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time Zanzibar experienced cholera. The
epidemic broke out in 1959 and killed 25,000 people, and in 1978
claimed lives of 300 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
