<HEADLINE> Lesotho Opposition Denies Ban on Marches to Royal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's opposition
Basutholand Congress Party (BCP) today vowed to disregard a ban
on marches to the royal palace imposed by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
A senior spokesman for the former ruling party Tsheliso
Makhakhe said the opposition would continue its protests until
its demands were met.
</P>
<P>
Barring people from seeing their king (King Letsie III) is
tantamount to denying Basotho their constitutional right to
peaceful demonstration and presenting petitions to the king as
head of state, Makhakhe said.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho government headed by Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle
Friday announced to ban all protest marches to the royal palace
in Maseru with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Deputy Prime Minister Paklitha Mosisili said
the planned processions to the palace were intended to bring King
Letsie III into disrepute by "involving him in the dust of
politics".
</P>
<P>
The ban followed protest marches which were held in the
capital this week by large groups of supporters of five main
political parties against the government.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle announced on June 9 the formation of the Lesotho
Congress for Democracy (LCD) and immediately transferred the
government power to the newly formed party.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle's moves sent shock waves in the tiny land-locked
mountain kingdom, forcing opposition parties to form a coalition
with the former ruling BCP, which unanimously condemned the move
and term it "unconstituional" or even as "coup d'etat".
</P>
<P>
Tsheliso Makhakhe, an opposition spokesman and executive
member of the BCP, said today that "I don't think there is any
constitution that allow a person in authority like the Prime
Minister (Mokhehle) to overthrow his own government and to form a
new party inside the chamber (parliament) without any reference
to the electorate."
</P>
<P>
The opposition said the government action signalled the coming
of draconian laws in Lesotho, and vowed to resist violation of
basic democratic rights by an "illegitimate" government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
