<HEADLINE> Round-up: Europe, America Squabble in Denver Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Differences between the
U.S. and its European allies on a wide range of issues come out as
leaders from the Group of Seven industrialized nations and Russia
met for a second day today.
</P>
<P>
The summit was convened against a backdrop of strong economy in
the United States, giving U.S. President Bill Clinton a chance to
boast for his achievement and teach the European allies lessons on
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the Europeans gave a cool shoulder to the U.S. for its
arrogance on matters relating to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), Bosnia and others.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit began with a working dinner on Friday
night, hosted by U.S. President Bill Clinton. European leaders
expressed concern to Clinton about U.S. plans to withdraw all its
troops from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has determined to pull out all its 8,500 strong troops
of Bosnia by June 1998, insisting that the Europeans should take
care of their own issues like Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
But when speaking at the dinner, French President Jacques
Chirac made it clear that the Europeans did not want to see
unilateral withdrawal of Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans fear that bloodshed may occur again if
peacekeeping forces were pulled out. The Bosnian Muslims, which
have obtained many heavy weapons from the U.S., were reportedly
prepared to launch new attacks against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The European leaders believe that military and civil goals of
the Dayton peace accords have just been partially achieved, so the
U.S. withdrawal would create a problem for the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Trans-Atlantic differences also remain on NATO's expansion.
Chirac told Clinton during a meeting on Friday that Romania should
be included in the first wave of expansion, while Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi told Clinton that Slovenia should not be
excluded.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has decided firmly to limit the enlargement to three
-- Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. seeks to reward Moscow on acquiescing the expansion of
NATO by giving a strong support to Russia's full participation.
Clinton said that Russia was "fully included" in the summit.
</P>
<P>
But France said that there was a consensus among the G-7
nations that Russia should not be included in discussions of
global economic and financial matters.
</P>
<P>
As host, Clinton also wants to rally support for cleaning up in
Chernobyl, Ukraine, after the 1986 nuclear reactor explosion.
Clinton is expected to ask for at least 300 million U.S. dollars
from G-7 members. European leaders are reluctant to pay more for
the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
