<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls on UN to Consider its Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today called on the
U.N. Security Council to respect its "political and security
concerns" during the inspection missions of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) disarming the country.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial published today, Al-thawra, mouthpiece of the
ruling Baath Socialist Party, said that "it is not right for the
Security Council... to make it (Iraq) its permanent victim
because of the council's weakness toward U.S. pressure."
</P>
<P>
It described Iraq's reservations over the UNSCOM's acts as
"serious and legitimate." It said these reservations emanate from
"genuine concerns over (Iraq's) national security and
sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis between Iraq and the Security Council has
been sparked by UNSCOM chief Rolf Ekeus, with "clear U.S. motives
behind", said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Ekeus, due to resign on July 1, will pay his last visit to
Iraq in his seven years' mission. He is expected to submit a
report to the Security Council on the arms inspection in Iraq
after his return.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Ekeus reported to the council that the
Iraqi side interfered with UNSCOM helicopters while carrying out
their inspection missions and barred the U.N. arms inspectors
from some compounds during the search for banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Saturday adopted a resolution
demanding the Iraqi government cooperate fully with UNSCOM arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said that it would impose new sanctions
unless weapons monitors certify Iraqi cooperation when they file
their new progress report on October 11. 
</P>
