<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Declines in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Violence by Muslim fundamentalists
in Egypt has firmly decline thanks to toughened security measures,
according to the latest edition of the Middle East Times.
</P>
<P>
The number of people killed dropped from 373 in 1995 to 174 in
1996, representing a 53.3 percent decrease, the English weekly
quoted an annual report of the Egyptian Organization of Human
Rights (EOHR).
</P>
<P>
Among the killed 53 were police officers, 34 Muslim militants,
69 civilians and 18 tourists, the EOHR report said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian security services succeeded in reducing the armed
Islamist groups' activities with successive strikes against their
strong-holds, resulting in the arrests or deaths of their top
leaders, it added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Interior Minister Hassan Al Alfi said last week that
4,392 Muslim fundamentalists had been arrested since a wave of
Muslim militant violence began sweeping the country in March
1992.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,175 people have been killed in the violence that
aimed to bring down the secular government of President Hosni
Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
