<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Roundup: Hasina Spends Rule Anniversary Quietly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Sheikh Hasina, Bangladesh's second
woman prime minister, completed her first year in office today
amidst poor economic performance but a rather quiet political
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The 50-year-old Hasina took power on June 23 last year after
her Awami League in the parliamentary polls defeated its main
political foe, former Prime Minister and Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) Chairperson Khaleda Zia.
</P>
<P>
Considering lofty election promises and a host of problems
inherited in the economic and socio-political life, "her work is
not so good, not so bad," said an observer here.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the new government has tried its utmost
to maintain political stability although it faced pressure and
protests from formidable political opponents over a series of
political and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
The issues raising controversy in politics mainly were related
to India and they include the Ganges water sharing treaty, transit
facilities to India and tribal insurgency in Chittagong Hill
Tracts.
</P>
<P>
Domestic issues which also created an uproar were an acute
power crisis, the disaster in the stock market, alleged repression
of the opposition and agitation by government employees over the
new office hours and the demand for new pay scales.
</P>
<P>
However, the main opposition BNP and other opposition groups
have so far failed to make any effective stir. Rather, the
opposition thought it prudent to buy more time before starting any
serious agitation using the scattered political and economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the third largest Jatiya Party (JP) is now caught in
a dilemma in determining the party's future. The mainstream JP led
by former President HM Ershad still maintains a soft line toward
the government but a dissident group led by Kazi Zafar is critical
of Hasina's administration.
</P>
<P>
Soon after assuming power, Hasina launched an "economic
diplomacy" to erase the sour memory of the "country of disaster,"
a label used by critics to describe Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister undertook nearly a dozen trips to foreign
countries, including China, the United States, India, Italy and
Turkey, where she spent most of her time meeting big companies and
business leaders and trying to get them to invest in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
However, "Bangladesh is likely to close fiscal 1997 with a
weakened reserve position, no significant structural reform
measures and a still unconvinced private sector," according to a
World Bank report.
</P>
<P>
The overall gross domestic product growth has been estimated at
5.7 percent in the current fiscal compared with 5.3 percent in the
last. This is primarily due to unprecedented performance of
agriculture, which is estimated to grow by 6 to as much as 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
But the manufacturing sector did not enjoy such glorious
performance. According to the Dhaka Chamber of Industries
estimates, the growth rate in the sector would be around 5.7
percent, the lowest in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank study said: "The ongoing depressed investment
and industrial activities, while raising concerns about the
sustainability of a higher economic growth, also highlight that
business confidence has not yet been restored."
</P>
<P>
The donor agency study also estimated that the export growth in
the current fiscal would remain below the government's projected
rate of 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the foreign exchange reserve position remains
critical. Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria said that at the end of
May this year, Bangladesh's foreign exchange reserves stood at
only 1.623 billion U.S. dollars, which was described by experts as
a "vulnerable" situation.
</P>
<P>
In the coming days, Hasina is going to face dual challenges,
said a political observer. "She has to maintain the much-needed
political stability to sustain the most-needed economic growth in
this least-developed country."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0043 </DOCNO>
