<HEADLINE> Tree Planting Marks Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 12,000 people took part
in tree planting along the Shenzhou section of the Beijing-Kowloon
Railway in north China's Hebei province today, marking the return
of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The activity was sponsored by the National Greening Committee
and the Forestry Ministry and is part of efforts to build a "green
corridor" along the new 2,553-km Beijing-Kowloon Railway, linking
Hong Kong and the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to plant trees on both sides of the railway in the
next four years so that by the year 2000, all areas two to five
kilometers along both sides of the railway line will have trees.
</P>
<P>
In the Jiangxi and Anhui province sections of the railway,
green belts have formed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Xu Youfang, the Forestry Minister,
hoped all local governments and departments along the railway to
put more funds into the undertaking and improve the management of
the project.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhou city in southeast Hebei province is well known for its
afforestation work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
