<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Children in U.S. Depict Hong Kong's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 21 (Xinhua) -- In the eyes of Chinese
children living in the United States with their parents, Hong
Kong's return to China is just like a kid returning to the embrace
of his mother.
</P>
<P>
Many children participating "Celebrating Hong Kong's Return"
painting contest, organized by the Chinese School Association in
the United States (CSAUS), personify the theme and entitle their
paintings "kid returning to mother." Under their pens, the mothers
are always young or middle-aged women, while the kids appear to be
babies or one-year-old just learning to walk. Whatever the age,
the mothers and kids are with black hair, black eyes and yellow
skin. Others draw animals to show the mother-and-kid relationship.
</P>
<P>
Of the 210 paintings shown at the Evergreen Publish and
Station, Monterey Park here, most are selected by some 80 Chinese
schools in 35 U.S. states and cities. Others are by children in
Chinese cities of Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The biggest painting was done collectively by 37 Chinese
children living in Boston, It is a scene of carnival of animals in
front of "peace woods." The painters' own photos are pinned at the
heart of flowers decorating the entire lower part of the picture.
</P>
<P>
Ling Qiu, organizer of the contest and master teacher at the
Hope Chinese School of Southern California, said that is is only
natural for overseas Chinese children to interpret Hong Kong's
return in a kid-returning-to-mother way, because their parents and
teachers say so and also because the Chinese culture cherishes
affection between mothers and children. Also a leader of the
CSAUS, she said members of the association offer classes after
school or during weekends to promote understanding of the Chinese
culture as well as teaching of the Chinese phonetic alphabet and
to simplify Chinese characters and standard Chinese pronunciation
(Mandarin). These schools accept both Chinese and American
children.
</P>
<P>
Ting Shao Kuang, a well-known Chinese painter now living in Los
Angeles, said after visiting the show that children's painting are
direct, real and innocent. "They paint what they think," he
said. "They have no convention to restrict them." Referring to art
education, the famous painter said that adult artistry would
hinder children's imagination and creativity. "Kids above 12 may
learn some adult skills," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
