<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Summer Grain Harvests for Three Consecutive Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to harvest 118
billion kg of grain this summer, a 3.5 percent increase or four
billion kg more than in 1996, hitting an all-time high, according
to the Chinese Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
This is the third consecutive year that China has had a good
summer grain harvest, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The output of summer oil-bearing crops is estimated at nine
million tons, an increase of nearly three percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the achievements to greater emphasis on
agriculture, improved science and technology, and good spring
weather.
</P>
<P>
This year's harvest is characterized by increases in growing
areas and per-unit outputs, increases in 21 of the 26 provinces,
autonomous regions, and municipalities, and record summer grain
highs in 15 of them, or nearly half of China's provinces.
</P>
<P>
The total growing area was 32.2 million ha, an increase of
about 666,000 ha. Inter-provincial harvesting by 30,000 combines
has also played a role, the ministry explained.
</P>
<P>
China had a record grain crop of 407.3 billion kg in 1984, but
the figure dropped to 379.1 billion kg the following year, and was
followed by fluctuations for several years. Grain production went
up to 446.2 billion kg in 1990, but again fell for another two
years.
</P>
<P>
Consistent emphasis on agriculture and encouraging farmers in
grain production are among the fundamental factors behind the good
summer harvest. The central government has introduced policies for
increasing input in agriculture and has raised the price of grain
several times in the past years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
