<HEADLINE> Vivid, Colorful Celebrations Held in Rain in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- People of all walks of life in
Hong Kong took part in various celebration activities today to
greet the return of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Hong Kong residents attended a gala festival,
jointly organized by more than 130 trade union councils at the
Victoria Park, on Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
A trade union official, surnamed Lee, said the fall of the
Union Jack on June 30 marks the end of the colonial rule of more
than one and a half centuries. He urged all people in Hong Kong to
contribute to the smooth transition of Hong Kong and its long-term
prosperity and stability with their wisdom and talents.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale float parade was held in Yuen Long, the "New
Territories" today. Nine decorated "dragons" played with a hundred
man-dressed lions, attracting large crowds of onlookers.
</P>
<P>
The Transit Train Railway Company began issuing commemorative
tickets today. Long queues lined up at every box office for the
special tickets, each of which bears a Bauhinia against the night
scene of Hong Kong Island on the obverse side and, on its reverse
side it carries the street scene of Hong Kong in the old days.
</P>
<P>
A young lady named Tsang cited the collection of such
commemorative tickets as a way to observe Hong Kong's return to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 returned Overseas Chinese performed solo
singing and dance items and boxing at one of the schools for
workers' children in Mong Kok, Kowloon, to express their joyous
feeling.  
</P>
</TEXT>
