<HEADLINE> Xinhua News Agency on Reunification of Motherland (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The "one country, two systems"
concept, which is being applied to Hong Kong, was initially
proposed for the Taiwan question.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary, Xinhua News Agency noted today that in
applying it to the Hong Kong question first, it marks a
significant step in the reunification of the motherland, and the
concept can also be applied to the Taiwan question.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping said that the only way to solve the Hong Kong and
Taiwan questions is to use the "one country, two systems"
principle, and the return of Hong Kong will prove the principle's
availability, it said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and Taiwan are questions that are left over from
history and resolving them is a matter of Chinese sovereignty and
is the common aspiration of the Chinese people, the commentary
said.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan question is different from the Hong Kong one, it
said, explaining that the former was left over from the civil war,
and is entirely an internal matter that should be solved by the
Chinese people themselves, but that the latter was left over by
the British colonialist invasion of China.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China and the Chinese government long
ago proposed the "peaceful reunification", and the "one country,
two systems" as the basic principles for solving the Taiwan
question, meaning that peaceful reunification across the Taiwan
Strait will be achieved through a principle of one China and
through political negotiations, the commentary said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua News agency on Reunification of Motherland (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The "one country, two systems" principle takes into
consideration both history and reality, and the interests of the
whole nation, the commentary noted. The smooth preparations for
Hong Kong's return over the past 13 years show that the principle
has won the popular support of the people, it said.
</P>
<P>
Allegations by Taiwan authorities that the principle could not
apply to Taiwan are groundless, the commentary noted, adding that
since 1979, the Communist Party of China and the Chinese
government have always advocated equal negotiations between the
two sides across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, in January, 1995 put forth the
eight-point propositions, proposing that talks be held to end the
state of hostility under the principle of one China, but the
Taiwan authorities proposed "splitting the country and ruling
under separate regimes", the commentary said, adding that they
also proposed "equal political entities without mutual
subordination". The Taiwan side has even gone so far as to try to
"join the United Nations" in an attempt to internationalize the
Taiwan question, but all the Taiwan authorities really want is to
get foreigners to interfere in cross-strait relations, the
commentary noted.
</P>
<P>
The one China principle is the base of and the prerequisite to
peaceful reunification of the motherland and it is a common
understanding of the overwhelming majority of the Chinese people
on both sides of the Taiwan Strait, the commentary stressed.
</P>
<P>
When China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong,
a series of policies on the "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
and a high-degree of autonomy, will be implemented under the
principle of "one country, two systems", it said.
</P>
<P>
The policies to be adopted for solving the Taiwan question may
be even more lenient, the commentary disclosed, while quoting Deng
Xiaoping as saying that Taiwan can retain its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The experiences of the past 20 years have shown that the
political stability and economic growth in China's inland areas
are conducive to the development and stability in Taiwan, Hong
Kong and Macao, and vice versa. the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
The realization of peaceful reunification of the two sides of
the strait according to the principle of "one country, two
systems" will cause no loss for the people of Taiwan, but enable
them to enjoy strong support from the mainland and its
international esteem and fame, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Descendant of National Hero Hails Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- When the Qing court signed the
Nanking Treaty, ceding Hong Kong to Britain in 1842, Lin Zexu, an
official who led the move to ban opium trade, ended a
distinguished career in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
Then, 143 years later, Lin Zexu's great great-grandson, Ling
Qing, who served as Chinese ambassador to the United Nations,
submitted the Sino-British Joint Declaration to the UN, stating
that China will resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong
on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"This is a historical coincidence," he said, "and a meeting
with destiny," reviewing the history of Hong Kong's being ceded to
Britain and the lengthy process of its return.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiating is a test of power," he said, "the Chinese
government during several periods wanted to get Hong Kong back,
but none of them was able to do it. After the founding of the new
China, the nation began to stand more firmly in the world."
</P>
<P>
Ling was a member of the first generation of new Chinese
diplomats and was a witness to the tremendous changes that took
place in Chinese society, its economy, and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
In referring to the Sino-British negotiations on the Hong Kong
question, he said proudly that the British had to give in, because
Deng Xiaoping insisted that "the issue of sovereignty is not
negotiable," and pointed out that, "No one can deny that China's
economic growth provided a basis for its recovery of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Ling is descended from Lin Zexu through his third son, Lin
Gongshu. His father, Lin Busui, served as an official in the late
Qing Dynasty and in the government of the Northern Warlords. Ling
took part in the War of Resistance against Japan, and later became
involved in political activities and foreign affairs. It was then
that he changed his name from Lin Moqing to Ling Qing.
</P>
<P>
"For me, the return of Hong Kong is, first and foremost a
matter of pride for Chinese, and a matter of dignity for a Chinese
diplomat at the same time," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
