<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   From Double-Deck Tram to Airport Expressway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is both traditional
and ultra-modern in public transport.
It is the only city in the world that has kept a double-deck tram
fleet.
</P>
<P>
Power-driven trams came to Hong Kong in 1904, running a 13-km
double track line along the north shore of Hong Kong Island from
east to west. The fare then was ten cents, a luxury few could
afford at a time when most people traveled on foot.
Nowadays, the fare has risen to 1.6 HK dollars, making tram the
cheapest means of transport.
</P>
<P>
The passage of time has thrown many old stuffs into
obsolescence. But the 93-year-old tram service has moved at its
own pace into the fast changing modern society.
</P>
<P>
The fleet of 163 trams now carries more than 310,000 passengers
a day. The tram is still a favorite of Hong Kong people for its
low price, convenience and a trace of nostalgia despite the fact
that it runs slowly and is without air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
Of course, the tram is only one of many choices in a highly
mobile city like Hong Kong, where an efficient multi-modal public
transport system handles over ten million passenger trips a day.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong boasts one of the world's busiest underground
railways -- the 43-km Mass Transit Railway, which transports over
two million passengers daily. The heavily-utilized rail system
runs across the Victoria Harbor to link 38 stations in Hong Kong
Island, Kowloon and the "New Territories." It came into full use
in the 1980s and now runs 19 hours a day. During the rush hours, a
train starts off in every two minutes.
</P>
<P>
A 34-km suburban railroad -- a section of the Kowloon-Canton
Railway -- carries commuters daily to new towns in the
northeastern part of the "New Territories." The railway has gone
through modernization since it began operation in 1910 -- from
single track to double tracks, from steam locomotives to diesel
locomotives and eventually to the present high-speed electric
train. In the late 1980s, an electric light rail line began
serving the northwestern part of the "New Territories."
</P>
<P>
A 109-year-old cable-hauled tram carries sightseers along the
tropical slope from downtown Central to the Victoria Peak where
people command a spectacular view of the vast cluster of tall
buildings on Hong Kong Island, the Victoria Harbor and Kowloon
beyond. It takes five minutes for the red carriages to move up and
down along the 1.4-km double-track line.
</P>
<P>
In addition to rails, many other transport services such as
buses, taxis and ferries offer Hong Kong commuters a good range of
choices at reasonable fares and different levels of comfort, speed
and convenience.
</P>
<P>
Like other metropolises, Hong Kong is faced with the pressing
problem of traffic congestion. More than 6.3 million people live
in an area of about 1,000 sq. km, and even worse, the hilly land
offers few plain plots.
</P>
<P>
There are 273 vehicles on every kilometer of road, almost the
highest traffic density in all cities around the world. The
average number of daily passengers via road transport, including
franchised buses, public light buses and taxis, reached 6.7
million at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Actually, quite a number of big infrastructure projects have
been completed or are under construction to improve efficiency of
public transport in tandem with economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Ferry used to be the only means of transport across the
Victoria Harbor, which links Hong Kong Island and the Kowloon
Peninsula. In the past, workers could not get back home when
rainstorms brought waterborne transport to a halt. Nowadays, three
cross-harbor tunnels can ensure different forms of transport to
run safely at any time.
</P>
<P>
The third crossing, the Western Harbor Tunnel, opened to
traffic in April this year. The 7.5-billion-HK dollars project can
handle 180,000 vehicles a day and boosts the cross-harbor capacity
by 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
A 34-km Airport Railway is being built to link Hong Kong
Island and Kowloon with the New Airport under construction at Chek
Lap Kok and Lantau an outlying island in the west of Hong Kong.
When put into use in 1998, the railway will offer two high-speed
services -- an Airport Express and a domestic mass transit service
-- which are expected to ease the urban traffic pressure.
</P>
<P>
A new railway stretching to the northwestern part of the "New
Territories" is being planned and the underground railway will
soon be extended to more new suburban towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
