<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Stops Using Freon for Refrigerators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran has launched a massive
program to replace freon, which is harmful to the ozone layer, in
manufacturing coolers and refrigerators, a local report said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Iran reported that the harmful gas will
be replaced by new gas which will leave no negative impact
on the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Ministry of Industries said that it has
allocated necessary foreign currency for shifting the production
lines. The ongoing development project aims to boost production
and improve quality of products in many household appliances.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the program is expected to complete
by the end of the next year.
</P>
<P>
Iran turned out 96,000 refrigerators and freezers during the
first two months of the current Iranian year (starting March 21),
showing an increase of 89 percent compared to the corresponding
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicted that the production of those articles
will stand at 1.2 million by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
To help Iran's replacement program, the United Nations has
granted 17 million U.S. dollars for eliminating substances that
destroy the ozone layer such as freon and CFC.
</P>
<P>
The figure is part of UN plans which have been launched
from 1996 to 2005.
</P>
<P>
Nasser Moharram Nezhad, Deputy President for Human Habitat of
Iran's Ecological Organization, said "by implementing plans aimed
at reconstructing ozone layer, all the substances that play a
role in destroying ozone layer will be eliminated from the
cycle of industrial and chemical products."
</P>
<P>
The official said that these plans were implemented in 1996
in the industrialized countries. In developing countries, too,
these plans will be fully implemented, with UN's assistance, by
the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Iran has pledged that it would reach the defined aims of
this program in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
