<HEADLINE> Australia's Stocks To Remain Strong in Coming Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia's share market is
likely to continue its recent strong performance during the coming
week while the Australian dollar may remain fairly steady.
</P>
<P>
Chief economist of AMP Investments Australia Ltd., Shane
Oliver, told reporters today that "there is nothing to stop those
gains of domestic equities to continue."
</P>
<P>
But Oliver could not anticipate how much the share market would
increase after it surpassed 2700 points on Friday and the U.S. Dow
Jones industrial index average lifted 19.45 points to 7796.15, the
Australian Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that economic data due out in the week would not
have a major impact on financial markets, but hesitancy could
begin to emerge in early July ahead of a U.S. Federal Reserve
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The question is whether the Federal Reserve of Australia will
raise interest rates again," he added.
</P>
<P>
Economists forecast yesterday that job vacancy figures would be
at any point between a fall of 5 percent and a gain of 4.5 percent
after it dropped 0.9 percent in the month of May.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar is likely to show little movement in the
coming week, having stabilized around 75 U.S. cents after dipping
on speculation about a monetary policy of easing, economists said.
</P>
<P>
According to an analysis by the Colonial State Bank, "with an
absence of factors driving the currency higher, the Australian
dollar may fluctuate between 74.5--75 U.S. cents over the week."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 75.13 U.S. cents Friday from
74.77 at the previous close and the All Ordinaries Index rose by
19.3 points to reach another record closing high of 2712.6.
</P>
</TEXT>
