<HEADLINE> Iran Trains 10,000 AIDS Counselors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran will have 10,000 AIDS
prevention counselors by the end of this Iranian calendar year
(March 20, 1998), the Persian daily Kar-o-Karegar reported today
</P>
<P>
This is part of the Iranian government's effort to prevent the
spread of the AIDS disease, Bahram Yeganeh, Secretary of the
Committee on Campaign against AIDS, was quoted as saying by the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 public health employees, psychiatrists and
specialists on infectious diseases have taken part in training
these people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Health Minister Ali Reza Marandi said last week that
only 1,047 people have been identified as HIV-positive in Iran
which has a population of 62 million.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 to 80 percent of the AIDS patients have acquired the
disease through sexual intercourse, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the blood and other biological products
offered through Iran's blood banks were contaminated with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have any problem in this regard. These products
are completely screened. They are especially free from AIDS
contamination," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Despite government attempts to educate the people through
AIDS counseling, health experts here have repeatedly criticized
the government's reluctance to use the mass media to inform the
people of ways to prevent the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The discussion of AIDS, especially its transmission through
sexual intercourse, is usually hushed in the mass media here.
</P>
<P>
The government-run radio and TV rarely discuss ways to
prevent the transmission of AIDS through sexual intercourse,
including the use of condoms, although condoms are imported by
Iran and openly sold at pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier report, 122 Iranians were killed by AIDS so
far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
