settle the row over the trial of two Libyans suspected of
involvement in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner over
Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people, he added.
</P>
<P>
Libya is under a U.N.-imposed air-traffic ban because of its
refusal to surrender the two men for trial in the U.S. and
Britain. Libya has been insisting that the men be tried in some
other country.
</P>
<P>
The recent OAU summit supports the Libyan proposals on ending
the dispute by conducting the trial in any country other than
Britain and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Meguid pointed out that he will also hold talks with
representatives of Security Council members and the U.N. Arab
group on the latest developments of the situation in Iraq. 
