<HEADLINE> No Cyprus Solution by This Fall: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- No solution to the protracted
Cyprus problem should be expected by Autumn this year, when the
first three rounds of direct talks are concluded, Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides said here today.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides was commenting on Saturday's press reports
that the U.S. and the United Kingdom expect that an agreement can
be reached on Cyprus problem by this Autumn.
</P>
<P>
Clerides told reporters that direct talks are expected to be
suspended in view of February 1998 presidential elections in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, President Clerides said he expects some developments
on the Cyprus issue in 1998, when a U.S. State Department team
will actively involved in efforts for a solution of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Radio Saturday quoted a Greek high-ranking diplomatic
source in New York as saying that the U.S. and Britain expect a
high level agreement to be reached by Autumn 1997 between Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, at their U.N.-sponsored
face-to-face talks, scheduled to begin on July 9, near New York.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Radio also reported today that the U.S. and Britain
were trying to coordinate their efforts for a set of ideas which
they will promote through the U.N. during the forthcoming direct
talks.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, it added, the newly-appointed
U.S. Presidential Emissary Richard Holbrooke had a meeting
Saturday in London with Britain's special envoy for Cyprus, Sir
David Hannay.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after Turkish troops occupied the
northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
