the coast of Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, have retreated from
S.Leone's territorial waters, according to a report reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal, which took place on Friday, came against the
background of three-hour closed door talks between Sierra Leone's
military junta and a high-level Ghanaian delegation to resolve the
crisis since the May 25 coup that toppled the 14-month-old
civilian government in S.Leone.
</P>
<P>
Details of the meeting have not been disclosed but the report said
Ghana is against military option in ending the impasse in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian Deputy Foreign Affairs Minister Victo Begho, who led the
four-man delegation in Freetown, was reported as warning that military
approach would be catastrophic for the west African sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The warships might have been withdrawn in
order to give a conducive atmosphere for the crisis to be resolved by
negotiation, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The warships arrived in Freetown in the wake of the coup when
troops of the west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG were
sent to take hold of the seaport and international airport in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Despite ECOMOG's military buildup, a constant reminder of the use
of force to restore the civilian government in Sierra Leone, west
African leaders maintain their desire to resolve the crisis by
peaceful means. 
