<HEADLINE> India to Ban Azo Dyes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A ban on the use of azo dyes in
the country will come into effect on June 23 this year, a
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The India Ministry of Environment has imposed the ban as part
of its effort to protect public health and the environment. The
use of azo dyes, widely utilized for dyeing natural and synthetic
fibers, leather, plastics, oils, fats, waxes, straw, timber, paper
and food items, is banned through a gazette notification issued by
the government on March 26 this year. The government had said the
ban would take effect 90 days after the issuance of the
notification.
</P>
<P>
The azo dyes are said to cause cancer and to be detrimental to
public health. The ban, which would be applicable throughout the
country, includes all substances containing these dyes, the
official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
