<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worst Yet to Come in Battle Against AIDS: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The worst is still to come in the
worldwide fight against AIDS, a World Health Organization (WHO)
expert warned at an international AIDS conference in Melbourne
today.
</P>
<P>
Peter Piot, executive director of UNAIDS at the WHO, told the
conference that there has been a dramatic increase in the number
of people living with AIDS in South and Southeast Asia and the
Pacific region, from 3 million in 1995 to 5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 8,500 people, including about 1,000 children, become
infected with the HIV virus every day around the world, said Piot,
a Belgian microbiologist who has worked in the HIV-AIDS field for
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
Piot told the three-day International AIDS Impact Conference
that 1.5 million people died from AIDS last year, accounting for a
quarter of all AIDS deaths since the beginning of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Half of new HIV infections globally involve women and the virus
is now "largely a heterosexually driven epidemic" internationally,
Piot said.
</P>
<P>
The official said about 23 million people worldwide are living
with HIV but not all countries are responding appropriately.
</P>
<P>
He warned that complacency is developing as new drugs and
treatments are discovered and some countries are denying the
existence of the problem.
</P>
<P>
Piot explained that new treatments shown to improve and extend
the lives of HIV sufferers are too costly for most sufferers in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
While these are a major breakthrough, resistance is developing
against new drugs and there is a race to continually improve them.
</P>
<P>
A vaccine against HIV infections is "dearly needed," but there
is still a long way to go before this is achieved, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
