<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-related Data (1): How Did HK Question Arise? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong question was the
result of the three unequal treaties signed by the Qing government
of China under coercion by the British imperialists.
</P>
<P>
On August 29, 1842, Britain forced the Qing government to sign
the Treaty of Nanking on ending the Opium War. The Qing government
was thereby compelled to permanently cede Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
In 1856, British and French allied forces launched the Second
Opium War, forcing the Qing government to sign the Treaty of
Peking on October 24, 1860. The Qing government was compelled to
permanently cede the Chinese territory south of the Boundary
Street on Kowloon Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, 1898, exploiting China's defeat in the Sino-Japanese
War and the establishment of "spheres of influence" in China by
foreign powers, Britain again forced the Qing government to sign
the Convention Regarding an Extension of the Hong Kong Territory,
"leasing" areas south of Shenzhen River and north of the Boundary
Street and more than 200 nearby isles (commonly called the "New
Territories", which comprise roughly 91 percent of the total area
of the Hong Kong region) for a term of 99 years until 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-related Data (2): HK Is Not a Colony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Up to the present, Britain has
ruled Hong Kong in a typical colonial fashion. However, this does
not mean Hong Kong is a colony.
</P>
<P>
A colony usually refers to a country that has lost its
sovereignty as a result of foreign rule and administration.
</P>
<P>
Since Hong Kong is part of the Chinese territory, the concept
of colony is not applicable to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Soon after China resumed her membership in the United Nations,
Huang Hua, then Chinese ambassador to the United Nations, wrote to
the chairman of UN Non-Colonization Special Committee on March 8,
1972, declaring, "The Hong Kong and Macao questions are left over
from history, the result of a series of unequal treaties imposed
on China by imperialism. Hong Kong and Macao are component parts
of the Chinese territory occupied by Britain and Portugal
respectively. The settlement of the Hong Kong and Macao questions
is a matter of China's sovereign right. By no means do Hong Kong
and Macao fall within the usual category of 'colony'."
</P>
<P>
The stand of the Chinese government on the question of Hong
Kong has won extensive international support. In November 1972,
the UN General Assembly adopted a resolution by a vote of 99 to 5
to exclude Hong Kong and Macao from the list of colonies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
