<HEADLINE> Australia's Housing Market Remains Subdued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia's housing market
remained subdued in April, with the number of first home buyers
falling ahead of the federal May budget and interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Agents have reported that the number of properties listed for
sale was either stable or down slightly for the month of April
while levels of inquiry were mostly unchanged, the Real Estate
Institute of Australia (REIA) said in a news release today.
</P>
<P>
But prices and rents rose slightly in most cities, sustaining a
steady increase in the past year in all mainland states and
territories, except Canberra.
</P>
<P>
REIA President Don Brindley said uncertainly in the lead-up to
the May budget contributed to the subdued market activity and he
called on the Reserve Bank of Australia to keep interest rates low
to allow the market to strengthen.
</P>
<P>
He said home loan affordability was at its highest level in
years and that housing oversupplies, which previously kept prices
weak, were nearly exhausted.
</P>
<P>
The 8.8-percent unemployment rate and high job uncertainty had
led to subdued confidence along with the federal budget, he said.
"Consumers were hoping for definitive vision and direction in the
May budget."
</P>
<P>
It has now been left to the Reserve Bank to provide the impetus
needed to encourage stronger economic growth in the country, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
