<HEADLINE> "It Will Be The Most Exciting Moment in My Life:" HK Barrister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Henry Hu, 77, will be among some
4,000 dignitaries at the historic handover ceremony to be held at
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center Extension at the
midnight of June 30.
As a member of society, the veteran barrister said, "it will be
the most exciting moment in my life to see the end of colonial
rule in Hong Kong and its return to the embrace of the
motherland."
</P>
<P>
In December 1984, Henry Hu personally witnessed the signing of
the Sino-British Joint Declaration in the Great hall of the People
in Beijing.
Moreover, as a government diplomat, he witnessed at the surrender
of the Japanese in 1945 and was also very excited, he added.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the transitional period of more than 10 years, he
said, in spite of those twists and turns, "the sweeping tides of
the handover can't be held back by grains of sand."
</P>
<P>
"Now a smooth transition is at sight and I'm fully confident in
Hong Kong's future," he said.
</P>
<P>
His confidence was justified by the Sino-British Joint
Declaration and the Basic Law, which stipulates that the laws
previously in force in Hong Kong will remain basically unchanged
after its return.
</P>
<P>
And in February this year the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC) published a decision on handling
the existing Hong Kong laws. In accordance with the decision, of
the more than 600 ordinances and over 1,000 pieces of subordinate
legislation, most will be retained and adopted as the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) laws.
</P>
<P>
Only 14 ordinances, which included those evolving British
colonial rule and some concerning elections formulated by the
British-Hong Kong government unilaterally, and certain articles of
10 others, such as the Bill of Rights Ordinance, the Public Order
Ordinance and the Societies Ordinance, will not be adopted as
HKSAR laws.
</P>
<P>
Hu acclaimed the decision as very generous, saying that it
reassured the people that after July 1 the Hong Kong laws will
basically remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
As one of the earliest Chinese barristers in Hong Kong, Hu has
frequent contacts with clients from overseas and felt that they
look forward to Hong Kong and have full confidence in the region
which is full of vitality and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
With the Basic Law as a guarantee, and an ever stronger
motherland as a powerful backing, people in Hong Kong have every
reason to foresee a more prosperous Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hu has been residing in Hong Kong for more than 40 years. In
1979, he was invited to Beijing to attend the 30th anniversary of
the People Republic of China as a member of the Legislative
Council and the Urban Council.
</P>
<P>
At present, he is a Standing Committee member of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), and a member of the Preparatory Committee for
the HKSAR. He is also a member of the Selection Committee for the
First HKSAR Government.
</P>
<P>
Apart from his legal profession and social work, he has spent
much of his time and all his wealth in the Shue Yan College he
founded in 1970's.
</P>
<P>
"Comparatively speaking, I have, maybe, a much stronger sense
of the Chinese nation. Loving the motherland is the right that
everyone cannot be deprived of."
</P>
<P>
"I will continue making efforts to contribute to the HKSAR," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
