<HEADLINE> Iraqi Dinar Devalues Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi dinar fell sharply against
U.S. dollar today, with one dollar changing 1,660 dinars.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest exchange rate for dinar against
U.S. dollar since the first shipments of humanitarian goods
arrived in the country in March when one dollar traded for
1,200-1,300 dinars.
</P>
<P>
Money exchangers here attributed the devaluation of the dinar
to the unclear prospect of U.N.'s lifting of the nearly
seven-year-old sanctions on Iraq imposed for its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Many residents of the Iraqi capital think that the sanctions
on Iraq will last until the next century.
</P>
<P>
The prices of daily necessities in Iraq such as egg and meat
went up consequently. The price of eggs per kilogram rose from 1,100
dinars a week ago to 1,400 dinars.
</P>
<P>
The daily life of the Iraqis has not been improved distinctly
although food and other humanitarian goods arrived in Iraq
continuously under the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal signed in May
1996.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Iraq is allowed to export 2 billion dollars
worth of oil over a six month period to buy food, medicine and
other humanitarian goods urgently needed in the country.
</P>
<P>
On June 8, Iraq and the U.N. exchanged the letters to renew
the oil-for-food deal. However, the extension of the deal for
another six months did not bring any hope for the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
Some money exchangers said the Iraqi government agreed with
the U.N. on the extension only because it "has no other choice"
at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
