<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Washington's top envoy here said the United States
has a "basically positive" outlook about Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
"We want the (Hong Kong's) transition to succeed." said Richard
Boucher, the U.S. consul-general in Hong Kong. "We believe our
interests will be protected. Hong Kong will prosper and China will
prosper as well."
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli authorities has decided to put limits
on the rights of 20 senior Palestinian officials in an effort to
stop what it called incitement, according to a report of the
state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Unidentified security sources were quoted as saying that those
on the blacklist are considered responsible for inciting recent
anti-Israel violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip as well as
for attacks on Jewish settlers and those Palestinian land dealers
who sell land to Jews.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations' Security Council adopted
a resolution Saturday demanding that Iraq cooperate fully with the
world body's arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the incident last week when the Iraqi Republican
Guards barred the U.N. arms inspectors from two compounds during a
search for banned weapons, the Security Council condemned the
Iraqi authorities.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council
authorized Secretary-General Kofi Annan to consult with potential
troop-contributing countries, mainly from Africa, on sending an
advance force to the Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The move came after informal consultations on a letter sent to
the council by Annan about a request from Gabon's President Omar
Bongo, who has been mediating negotiations between the Government
of Congo and the rebel militias.
</P>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, U.S. -- Finance ministers from seven Western
industrialized countries Saturday pledged to promote stability in
global financial markets by enhancing cooperation and regulation.
</P>
<P>
In a final report to the G7 leaders attending the Denver
Summit, the finance ministers said that much progress has been
made in promoting the stability of the global financial markets
since last G7 summit in France in 1996.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Delegations from Bolivia, Colombia,
Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela will start a meeting in this city
next Monday to plan the eradication of foot-and-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
The delegations will report on the programs implemented in
their countries in curing the cattle sickness and guidelines to
follow in the next months, according to the Colombian Agriculture
Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Leaders of the Albanian coalition parties will meet
here on Monday to sign an accord for guaranteeing the June 29
elections, organizers of the meeting announced today.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting will be Tritan Sheu, chairman of
President Sali Berisha's Democratic Party, Fatos Nano of the
Socialist Party and leaders of the opposition to the president.
</P>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, U.S. -- Leaders of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations and Russia Saturday called on the Balkan
leaders to protect peace in Bosnia and would face a cut-off of aid
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
A draft statement, which is to be approved by the leaders of the
U.S., Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Canada, Russia and the
European Union, urged the implementation of the civil aspects of the
Dayton peace accords signed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- A photo exhibition entitled "The Return of
Hong Kong to the Motherland" opened here at Tanzania National
Museum.
</P>
<P>
Opening the exhibition, the Tanzania Minister for Education
and Culture, Kapuya said, "we are here to celebrate the return of
Hong Kong to China which will officially take place on July 1,
1997." 
</P>
</TEXT>
