<HEADLINE> Crown Postage Not Valid After June 30: Postmaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Robert Footman, postmaster
general of Hong Kong, announced here today that with effect from
July 1, all Hong Kong postage stamps and franking machine
impressions bearing signs of British ruling sign will not be valid
for prepayment of postage in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to the postmaster, the British ruling sign includes
the Royal Cypher, the British Queen's portrait or the Crown.
</P>
<P>
In January, Hong Kong began to issue a new set of definitive
stamps to substitute the Queen's portrait from general sale.
</P>
<P>
The set of new stamps comprise 16 denominations, featuring a
continuous stretch of the waterfront of Hong Kong with 13
low-value stamps in small format depicting a day scene while the
three high-value stamps in large format depicting a night scene.
</P>
<P>
The new stamps now in use will be valid after June 30 this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
