<HEADLINE> Motorola Employs Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The US's Motorola has employed 90
women workers who were laid off at money-losing state-owned
enterprises in Tianjin, north China's port city, helping the local
government find jobs for out-of-work people.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjin Motorola subsidiary is the largest company owned
exclusively by American investors in the city. The company, after
recruiting 60 laid-off women workers not long ago, decided to
recruit 30 more.
</P>
<P>
The laid-off women workers have a great potential in adjusting
themselves to a new working environment, and they did well, local
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Motorola Tianjin now has about 7,000 Chinese employees, most of
whom are college graduates, and has never employed these kind of
women workers before. These women are hard-working, and they had
experiences in running a sophisticated production line, an
executives said. The women are now running an assembly line and
had a new record in daily output on the line.
</P>
<P>
Other joint ventures in Tianjin have shown an interest in
Motorola's move, and foreign-funded enterprises have become a
major place for laid-off workers to look for work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
