<HEADLINE> S. Korean President Leaves for U.N. Session, Mexico Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
left here this afternoon to attend a special United Nations
session on the environment and will continue on to Mexico for a
state visit.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in New York from June 23 to 26 for the special
session of the U.N. general assembly on the environment, kim is
expected to meet with other participating state leaders, including
U.S. President Bill Clinton, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, French President Jacques Chirac, Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi and Hungarian Prime Minister Gyula Horn.
</P>
<P>
He will then fly on to Mexico for a three-day visit to boost
economic cooperation between the two countries. South Korean and
Mexico will sign agreements waivering visa requirements for
diplomats and public officials and establishing a joint
trade-industry cooperation committee.
</P>
<P>
A team of 34 top South Korean business executives will
accompany Kim on his trip to Mexico to support the president's
"economic diplomacy." 
</P>
