<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Prospects for Hong Kong's Shipping Industry After Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The continuation of China's open
policy and Hong Kong's economic stability will contribute to a
bright future for the region's shipping industry after its return
to China, industry executives here say.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Hong Kong handled 13.42 million standard containers,
up 6.9 percent from 1995, statistics from the Hong Kong Port
Development Board show.
</P>
<P>
The total container throughput this year is expected to
increase by 8.5 percent over last year, the executives say.
</P>
<P>
Of the three major arteries of Hong Kong's shipping industry --
Hong Kong-America, Hong Kong-Europe and Hong Kong-Asia, Hong
Kong-Asia shipping lines have had a prominent performance in
recent years thanks to rapid economic growth in the Asia-Pacific
region. In the first two quarters of this year, cargo throughput
on these lines is expected to grow by about eight percent.
</P>
<P>
And marine trade still constitutes the lifeblood of Hong Kong's
economy, according to the executives.
</P>
<P>
As about 45 percent of China's imports and exports is done via
Hong Kong, the region's status as the port of China's entrepot
trade will remain unchanged so long as China continues its policy
of opening up and reform, the executives say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
