<HEADLINE> Airline Landing Rights Row Rages Between Kenya, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A diplomatic row between Kenya
and Zambia appears imminent following a breakdown of talks
between the two countries over landing rights for Kenya Airways
(KQ) in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
However, a committee was expected to be set up by Tuesday to
see how a revenue-sharing method can be used to end the
stalemate, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian authorities sent a telegraphic message two days
ago to the Kenyan government asking KQ, Kenya's national carrier,
to stop its Monday and Thursday flights into Zambia's capital
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
KQ sources said the row was caused by the strong "attack" on
the Zambian market by the Kenya Airways, which usually makes four
flights into Lusaka in a week.
</P>
<P>
The economic rivalry is so major that Aero Zambia wants KQ to
either reduce the number of its flights or devise a
revenue-sharing mechanism beneficial to both airlines.
</P>
<P>
The dispute has resulted in the barring of Kenya Airways
flights into Lusaka. Last month, a KQ flight was turned back by
air traffic controllers in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held a meeting three weeks ago to resolve the
stand-off, but ended in vain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
