<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Languages In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai Province
has made an effort to encourage the use of ethnic languages in
recent years among its many ethnic groups who occupy 98 percent of
the province's land areas and 25 percent of the province's
population.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetans, Mongolians and Salars all have their own spoken
or written languages. To provide more opportunities for ethnic
people to learn their languages, the province has launched a
number of newspapers and magazines in those languages.
</P>
<P>
Local television and radio stations have also provided special
channels in Tibetan, offering programs on science, the law,
education, technology and economics.
</P>
<P>
To help ethnic people develop the economy and their culture,
Qinghai Publishing House has published 3.5 million copies of more
than 300 titles in ethnic languages.
</P>
<P>
Each year, over 2,000 ethnic teachers graduate from local
teachers' colleges, and go on to play a leading role in bilingual
education in primary and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province detailed regulations on ethnic
language protection and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
