<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner-Mongolia Show "Red Cards" to Unqualified Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Some senior local officials in the
Inner-Mongolia Autonomous Region in north China will be removed
from their posts because of poor work and bad results.
</P>
<P>
This move was taken by the region to stop corruption and poor
working efficiency within the governmental body, local officials
said.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent evaluation of work done by each
department and bureau of the regional government, the senior
officials in the health department and the metallurgical and
machinery-building department will be demoted.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all local newspapers front-paged the news, which became
a hot topic for residents in Huhhot, capital of the region.
</P>
<P>
"Officials should be promoted according to their real
capability and work done. Those unqualified should be removed, so
as to maintain a high-efficiency government," a worker whose first
name is "Yun" said.
</P>
<P>
"This makes the government officials work hard, if they want to
keep their ranks and positions. That is a great idea in reforming
the government," businessman Chen Jian said.
</P>
<P>
The region has become the second in China to introduce such
methods to evaluate the work by senior officials. The first was
neighboring Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
"This will help improve the work efficiency of the government,
and have all government officials do their best," Liu Mingzu,
chairman of the region, said.
</P>
<P>
According to the evaluation methods, each department has to
work out a plan at the beginning of a year, and local government
will grade its senior officials at the year end based on what has
been done.
</P>
<P>
"Whether an official will be promoted or not, or demoted, it
depends on his work," Qin Gang, a senior official in charge of the
evaluation, said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
