<HEADLINE> Israel Limits Rights Of Senior Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli authorities has
decided to put limits on the rights of 20 senior Palestinian
officials in an effort to stop what it called incitement,
according to a report of the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Unidentified security sources were quoted as saying that those
on the blacklist are considered responsible for inciting recent
anti-Israel violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip as well
as for attacks on Jewish settlers and those Palestinian land
dealers who sell land to Jews.
</P>
<P>
Among those on the list are Palestinian Justice Minister
Freih Abu Middein and a number of the legislative Palestinian
Council.
</P>
<P>
The sources did not specify the range of rights to be
limited, but said that the move would not include preventing
those people from entering Israel or from crossing between the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli authorities has occasionally placed restrictions on
the privileges senior Palestinian officials enjoy under the Oslo
Accords. Earlier this month, Israel canceled the VIP card of
Col. Tawfik Tirawi, head of the Palestinian General Security
Service in the West Bank, claiming that he was responsible
allegedly for the killings of three Palestinians who have sold
land to Jews.
</P>
<P>
The VIP card enables the holder to enter Israel from the
West Bank and Gaza Strip freely and to cross into Jordan
and back with no restrictions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
