<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falling Imports Could Impair Foreign Trade: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior economist in Beijing
called for awareness of imports, which have dropped during the
past five months in contrast with the rapid growth of exports,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The lastest report from the General Administration of Customs
said China's exports surged 26.4 percent in the first five months
to 65.5 billion US dollars, while imports decreased 1.2 percent to
51.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although it is reasonable to gloat over increasing exports, a
continuous drop in imports is nothing to brag about. It harms the
long-term development of China's foreign trade, said Zhu Baoliang,
deputy division chief of the State Information Center's economic
forecasting department.
</P>
<P>
A continued surplus in foreign trade coupled with rising
overseas investment will help the renminbi rise. In return, it
will hurt the exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu called attention to two patterns characterizing imports in
the first five months. General trade imports have fallen while
processing trade has risen, and finished industrial product
imports have ebbed while primary products gained.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded processing enterprises continue to receive more
orders from abroad and are exempt from domestic market
fluctuations, so their raw material imports are expected to remain
high.
</P>
<P>
Tariff reductions on primary goods stimulated imports of such
products.
</P>
<P>
Decreased imports from the State sector seemed overshadowed by
growth in the processing industry.
</P>
<P>
"slackened performance of State enterprises is causing the
import decline," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
State enterprises constitute about 85 percent of general trade
imports in China.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient demand because of moderately tight macro-economy
impedes enterprises from buying from abroad.
</P>
<P>
As domestic machinery, electronics products and textiles
glutted the market and quality improved, demand for foreign
industrial products decreased, zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He continued that the second half of 1997 will continue to
drive the economy's growth. As a result, machinery and
transportation equipment imports should increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
