<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy  by Zhang Tiegang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Washington's top envoy here said
the United States has a "basically positive" outlook about Hong
Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
"We want the (Hong Kong's) transition to succeed. We want the
approach of 'one country, two systems' to succeed. We believe our
interests will be protected. Hong Kong will prosper and China will
prosper as well," said Richard Boucher, the U.S. consul-general in
Hong Kong, in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
A career diplomat, Richard Boucher came here last August from
his post in Cyprus as American ambassador.
</P>
<P>
As consul-general, he is tasked with steering Washington's
relations with Hong Kong prior and after its return to China on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
"Our outlook (on the future of Hong Kong) is basically
positive," the consul-general said in his Garden Road office.
</P>
<P>
The large U.S. business community in Hong Kong, including the
local American Chamber of Commerce, shares this view. A recent
pool of the community shows that 95 percent believe Hong Kong's
economic prospects are favorable.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong "can continue to play the important role that it has
been playing as a financial center, as a trade center and as a
place where projects are brought together," Boucher said, adding
that "the prospect is quite good."
</P>
<P>
In his view, Hong Kong can not only maintain but also grow its
"ability to organize manufacturing quickly, to bring together
international financing, foreign technology and foreign expertise,
and to put together all of these in a package that results in
products that are designed for a particular market, made quickly
and delivered on time and quickly."
</P>
<P>
"We see lots of good factors," he said. U.S. businessmen view
Beijing's offer of "one country, two systems," "a high-degree of
autonomy" and maintenance of Hong Kong's way of life for 50 years
not only as key components of its social system but also as
important elements of the business environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Boucher acknowledged that the United States has a dispute
with Hong Kong over intellectual property rights and has concerns
over some issues after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
However, Boucher said, "Our basic policy framework is to say
that the (Sino-British) Joint Declaration and the Basic Law (of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region) are the right
commitments. As long as they are carried out, we think things will
be OK."
</P>
<P>
A total of 40,000 Americans work and live in Hong Kong, and the
American Chamber of Commerce here is the largest of its kind
outside the United States. Last year alone, more than 700,000
Americans visited Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We have found ever increasing economic ties between the United
States and Hong Kong," the consul-general said, "We have very
significant investment in Hong Kong -- 14 billion U.S. dollars."
</P>
<P>
According to Mr. Boucher, the United States is Hong Kong's
second largest trading partner. Every year, it buys about seven
billion U.S. dollars of goods from Hong Kong and 31 billion worth
of reexport goods via Hong Kong, usually from China's inland
areas, while Hong Kong buys 15.5 billion U.S. dollars of goods
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
A total of more than 1,200 American companies operate in Hong
Kong, including 450 which run regional operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
For the Americans, Hong Kong is not only a center for doing
business with China's interior areas and Hong Kong itself but also
a regional Asian center, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are very much involved in Hong Kong in a way it is now and
the way that I think really helps support not only U.S. relations
with Hong Kong but relations with China as well," he said, noting
that U.S. interests "are really no different" from those of people
in Hong Kong and in the rest of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
