<HEADLINE> Stock Issue Helps Mushroom Company Expand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The largest mushroom grower in
Asia plans to sell stock in the domestic market to raise money for
expansion, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Yantai Jiufa Edible Fungus Co is expected to float A shares,
which absorb capital from domestic investors, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The company, a Sino-Italian joint venture set up in 1993, sells
fresh mushrooms to Japan, frozen ones to Italy and Germany, and
canned ones to the United States.
</P>
<P>
With a fixed investment of 100 million yuan (12 million US
dollars), the company churns out 3,000 tons of mushrooms a year.
They sell for about 16,000 yuan (1,927) per ton.
</P>
<P>
Qu Xiuren, head of the Yulindian County government, said the
company's annual production capacity would double if sufficient
funds were guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The company is a typical export-oriented firm set up by farmers
on China's east coast.
</P>
<P>
"We need investment, foreign or domestic," Qu said.
</P>
<P>
While the county depends on agriculture, its geographic
location has turned it into a natural export base of green
food. Green food is the Chinese equivalent of organic food, which
is grown without chemical fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Located on the northeast tip of Shandong Peninsula, it has sea
access to Japan and South Korea, which share increasing demand for
organic food and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Qu predicted world demand for the company's mushrooms would not
subside because of the low price and high quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
