<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heath Optimistic on Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Former British Prime Minister Sir
Edward Heath said he was very upbeat on Hong Kong's future after
its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure the prospects of Hong Kong will be very good. The
rest of the world believes this," Heath said in an exclusive
interview with Xinhua in Salisbury Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This is showed by the amounts of investments going into Hong
Kong and the People's Republic (of China)."
</P>
<P>
"It is also showed by the fact that the prices of stocks and
shares are continuously rising, which means people have got
confidence in the future of the People's Republic and Hong Kong
working together," said the 81-year-old veteran British statesman.
</P>
<P>
Heath, who was the first British prime minister to propose the
smooth transition of Hong Kong in 1997, said, "I always recognize
that, of course, in 1997 Hong Kong would be returned to the
People's Republic. It was absolutely right that we should accept
this."
</P>
<P>
"I think the people of Hong Kong understand the situation very
clearly. They regard the People's Repubic as their homeland," said
Heath, who, during his term of office as prime minister,
established full diplomatic relations with China in 1972.
</P>
<P>
On the "one country, two systems" concept created by the late
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, Heath said the concept is a very
good formula, because it takes account of the differences between
Hong Kong and the mainland (of China).
</P>
<P>
It means the two can closely work together, because they have
acknowledged the different circumstances, which have existed
between them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Heath dismissed viewpoints by some critics on Hong Kong'
future, saying their criticisms are not justified "when we look at
the figures for trade, investment and general development. The
rest of the world has confidence and they would be very satisfied
with the results."
</P>
<P>
On the prospects of the Sino-British relations after Hong
Kong's return to China, he said "I want them to be as good as
possible. There is no reason why they shouldn't. No reason at all."
</P>
<P>
"Now Hong Kong is returning to China. There will be another
good opportunity for Sino-British trade to increase very
substantially. We want to increase trade now straight away. We
want to do as much trade as possible," said Heath.
</P>
<P>
The well-known British statesman, who visited China 21 times
and met Chinese President Jiang Zemin and the late Chinese leaders
Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping, stressed that he was really
impressed with China's dramatic changes achieved through economic
reforms initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"The reforms are very successful. They have transformed China's
economic position and this process will continue in the future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The former British prime minister is going next week to Hong
Kong to attend the handover ceremony as a member of the official
British delegation and is planning his 22nd visit to China later
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
