<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Iraq to Cooperate With Arms Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations'
Security Council adopted a resolution today demanding that Iraq
cooperate fully with the world body's arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the incident last week when the Iraqi Republican
Guards barred the U.N. arms inspectors from two compounds during a
search for banned weapons, the Security Council condemned the
Iraqi authorities.
</P>
<P>
It said refusing access to sites designated by the U.N. Special
Commission constitutes a clear and flagrant violation of the
provisions of relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council demanded that the Iraqi government allow
the Special Commission inspection teams "immediate, unconditional
and unrestricted access" to all areas, facilities, equipments,
records and means of transportation which they wish to inspect in
accordance with the mandate of the Commission.
</P>
<P>
It demanded that Iraq give immediate, unconditional and
unrestricted access to officials and other people under the
authority of the Iraqi government whom the Special Commission
wishes to interview, so that it may fully discharge its mandate.
</P>
<P>
At today's Security Council meeting, Chinese Permanent
Representative Qin Huasun said that the Chinese government
supports the Special Commission in fulfilling its mandate in
strict compliance with the relevant resolutions of the Security
Council, and urges Iraq to fully implement the relevant
resolutions of the Council and better cooperate with the Special
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Qin said that the legitimate security concerns of Iraq should
be respected by all parties, Security Council Resolution 687
should be fully implemented, Iraq's sovereignty, territorial
integrity and political independence respected, and the joint
statement signed by the Special Commission and Iraq in June last
year implemented in real earnest.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions against Iraq have already been enforced for six
years. According to the report of the Special Commission, in the
past six years, Iraq has basically maintained cooperation with it
and the Special Commission has also made great progress in
carrying out the mandate entrusted to it by the Security Council.
Moreover, Iraq has cooperated with the commission in most of the
more than 40 inspections conducted over the recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, we should consider gradually lifting
sanctions against Iraq to alleviate its humanitarian difficulties,
Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Qin stressed that the Chinese government always opposes the
willful imposition and threat of sanctions against a country.
This was proved to be counterproductive rather than serving to
solve problems appropriately.
</P>
<P>
The task of the Special Commission is to determine whether Iraq
has complied with U.N. orders to destroy its long-range missiles
and other weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Republican Guards barred the U.N. arms inspectors
from two compounds during a search for banned weapons on June 10
and 12.
</P>
<P>
Following this incident, the United States and Britain
submitted a resolution to ban Iraqi soldiers, police and
intelligence officers from traveling abroad without permission and
to suspend reviews of the sanctions until October.
</P>
<P>
But the Russian Federation, China and France opposed further
punitive measures. After intensive consultations Friday and today,
the Security Council adopted the resolution, sending a strong
signal to the Iraqi authorities rather than imposing more severe
sanctions on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
