<HEADLINE> UN Chief to Consult on Advance Force to Republic of Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council today authorized Secretary-General Kofi Annan to consult
with potential troop-contributing countries, mainly from Africa,
on sending an advance force to the Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The move came after informal consultations on a letter sent to
the council by Annan about a request from Gabon's President Omar
Bongo, who has been mediating negotiations between the Government
of Congo and the rebel militias.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after consultation of the Security
Council, Annan said: "I think the Security Council has agreed with
me that the situation in the country is urgent and we should do
whatever we can to assist."
</P>
<P>
"So we will be consulting the governments in the region that
have indicated that they are prepared to contribute to a force to
try and stabilize the situation and ensure that there is a
ceasefire."
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said that he would report back to the
Security Council the availability of troops, the structure and
mandate of the proposed force, and how it would be financed.
</P>
<P>
The aim would be first to send in an advance force quickly,
which could then be built up with reinforcements from other
countries, Annan added.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between the troops of the government and the rebel
militias erupted on June 5, in which hundreds have been
killed. The two sides agreed on Friday to extend a truce for a
further week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
