<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: "New Territories" Residents Greet Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- In Yuen Long of the "New
Territories", people from 26 villages of Pat Heung Township are
building a stone column in Sheung Tsuen Park to commemorate the
handover of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a 32.4-meter-high lookout tower named "Tower in
Commemoration of Hong Kong's Handover" is now 90 percent ready in
the Seaside Park of Tai Po. Both erections are scheduled for
completion a few days before the handover.
</P>
<P>
The midnight on June 30 will be an exciting moment for many
when China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
However, none is more excited than the residents in the "New
Territories".
</P>
<P>
"We've been waiting for the day for generations, ever since our
ancestors shed blood and sacrificed lives to defend this piece of
land against the British aggressors," said Chairman of the Pat
Heung Rural Committee Philip Lai, who led his fellow villagers in
donating over one million HK dollars (128,000 U.S. dollars) to
erect the stone column.
</P>
<P>
In 1899, the British troops who had occupied Hong Kong Island
in 1841 expanded their invasion toward the north but met with
fierce resistance from local residents.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that the local villagers organized
themselves with simple arms to fight the gun-equipped British
troops. After a few battles the villagers lost, leaving several
hundred dead.
</P>
<P>
some 100 meters from the site of the column there is a memorial
temple, in which two black tablets bear 40-odd names -- martyrs
during those battles. For nearly 100 years they have been
enshrined, secretly of course, as "righteous persons".
</P>
<P>
"Although we have lived under colonial rule for more than 100
years, we never obeyed that rule in the heart. We are all
descendants of the Dragon, we are all Chinese," said Philip Lai.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the founding of the People's Republic of
China in 1949, the local residents have been celebrating China's
National Day every year, in their own way.
</P>
<P>
In another township named Ping Shan, which neighbors Pat Hung,
people are also busy preparing for handover celebrations. Most
residents in Ping Shan belong to the Tang Family, which is one of
the largest clans in the "New Territories".
</P>
<P>
Actually the Tang Family started their celebrations more than a
year ago. On the early morning of October 1 last year, a few
thousand members of the Tang Family gathered in front of the
Tang's Temple for their first ever celebration of the 47th
National Day of the PRC.
</P>
<P>
When the five-star red flag was raised to the music of the
Chinese National Anthem, the villagers set off a 15-meter-long
string of firecrackers and queued up in front of the flagpole to
take pictures.
</P>
<P>
Head of Hung Who Village Tang Chin Peng said that Hong Kong's
handover to the motherland is a must and all the villagers feel
proud of it.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Public Fund of the Tang Family spent over
60,000 HK dollars (about 7,700 U.S. dollars) to erect the
16-meter-high flagpole. From now on the Tang Family will hold
flag-raising ceremony on every National Day.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three-year-old Tang Sing Sze said: "The hoisting of the
red flag means a lot to us. Our country is strong and powerful."
</P>
<P>
"In 1949 when New China was founded, some villagers here raised
a red flag to do their part in national celebration. However, the
British Hong Kong Government quickly sent spies here to collect
information and tried to arrest those who participated in raising
the flag.
</P>
<P>
"On every October 1 since then, we presented our blessing to
the motherland in the heart. You can never cut off anyone from his
motherland. Now we can celebrate the National Day in public and
with proud," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in 1899, ancestors of the Tang Family allied with
people from 39 local villages to fight the British aggressors, and
many of them died in battle.
</P>
<P>
An announcement by the Tang Family said: "For nearly 100 years,
the Tang Family, like other fellow villagers, have always wished
our motherland strong and powerful, wished the historical
humiliation be erased and our lost land recovered. Now the day is
about to come."
</P>
<P>
Member of the "New Territories" Committee for Celebrating Hong
Kong's Return to China Tang Siu-Tong said the great event will be
grandly celebrated in all the nine districts of the "New
Territories" in June and July.
</P>
<P>
Today in Yuen Long District, tens of thousands of people
swarmed to streets and public areas to participate in various mass
performances and competitions, and enjoy the dancing of nine
dragons and 100 lions -- the most grandiose of all such
performances ever held in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
