<HEADLINE> Roundup: Blue Chips on BSE Attract Brisk Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The sensitive index on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market managed to move up further by
53 points even after crossing the psychological 4,000 barrier
perceived as a resistant level during the week.
</P>
<P>
It was mainly due to sharp upswings in index-based heavy
weighted scrips and bonus news from Reliance Industries.
</P>
<P>
A select few blue chips attracted brisk activity and cornered
sharp gains preventing the expected reaction in share prices which
had pushed the sensitive index up by whopping 305.88 points in a
fortnight from May 29 to June 13.
</P>
<P>
The initial hesitancy, which led by a hefty fall in ITC, was
completely wiped out as foreign institutional investors and local
operationors started hectic purchases of the front-line scrips
such as ITC, TELCO, Mah &AMP; Mah, RIL, Tata Steel and software
shares.
</P>
<P>
Activity was largely confined to front-line shares which helped
a substantial rise in the BSE sensitive index.
</P>
<P>
The last two sessions also attracted brisk volume of business
with RIL in the lead on the company's announcement of a board
meeting on June 26 to consider the much-awaited bonus issue.
</P>
<P>
The news generated hectic buying in this scrip and other
heavy-weighted shares.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index, which closed fractionally lower at
4,025.41 on Monday, later rose sharply to cross 4,100-mark at
4,148.86 on Wednesday, before settling down at 4,083.04 at the
weekend as against last weekend's closing of 4,029.99, showing a
net gain of 53.05 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index firmed up by 26.56 points to end the week at
1,753.27 from last weekend 's closing of 1,726.71.  
</P>
</TEXT>
