<HEADLINE> G7 Finance Ministers Urge For Financial Markets Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Denver, Colorado, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Finance ministers from
seven Western industrialized countries pledged today to promote
stability in global financial markets by enhancing cooperation and
regulation.
</P>
<P>
In a final report to the G7 leaders attending the Denver
Summit, the finance ministers said that much progress has been
made in promoting the stability of the global financial markets
since last G7 summit in France in 1996.
</P>
<P>
They said that progress has been made in four areas:
international regulatory cooperation, risk management and
market transparency, prudential standards in emerging economies
and electronic money.
</P>
<P>
Looking beyond the Denver Summit, the ministers demanded that
efforts to strengthen the international financial system continue
and identified two areas warranting particular efforts.
</P>
<P>
On cooperation among supervisors for the markets, they
encouraged the international regulatory bodies and national
supervisors to reach agreement and implement their proposals in
this respect.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged to assess the impediments to information
sharing and called on the international regulatory bodies, the IMF
and the World Bank, to report to G7 finance ministers' meeting in
next April on their contribution to the financial systems and
prudential supervision in emerging economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
