<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Create Fine Business Environment for Hong Kong: Senior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Official
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Denise Yue Chung-Yee, a senior
government official, said she is confident in Hong Kong's trade
prospects in accordance with the "one country, two systems"
principle after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) provides that Hong Kong will enjoy a high degree of
autonomy after July 1.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hong Kong will still be an independent member of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) and an independent tariff zone.
Investment from Hong Kong in the inland areas will continue to
enjoy preferential treatment granted to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
All this will fully ensure Hong Kong's status as an
international trade center after it returns to the embrace of the
motherland, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Trade and Industry Branch Yue works with is a key economic
policy-making department in Hong Kong. Its major duties include
the formulation of policies on external trade, industry and
commerce, intellectual property rights and the protection of
consumers' rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
In her forties, Yue is the youngest female official at the
director-level in the HKSAR Government.
</P>
<P>
She believes that external trade is a pillar for Hong Kong's
economy and requires tremendous efforts of her branch.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong develops trade cooperation with other parts of the
world and safeguards its own interests mainly through the WTO. In
1986, it joined the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT)
as an independent member and became a founding member of the WTO
after the GATT changed into the WTO in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the interior areas of China and Hong Kong has
grown rapidly since China initiated the policy of reform and
opening-up in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
"In 1985, the interior areas replaced the United States as Hong
Kong's largest trade partner and are exerting an increasing
influence on Hong Kong's economic development," she said.
</P>
<P>
Yue deems it imperative to increase economic exchanges and
cooperation with the interior areas, study the new trend toward
trade development and assess the impact of new measures on foreign
trade taken in interior areas on Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
In April 1996, she said, the Trade Department set up a special
body to handle trade relations between the interior areas and Hong
Kong, in an effort to promptly learn the latest information on
trade and foreign investment policies in the interior areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials of the Trade Department and the Industry
and Commerce Branch of Hong Kong have paid frequent visits to the
interior areas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Though most labor-intensive industries and industries with a
low added value in Hong Kong have moved to areas in southern China
over the past few years, this does not mean an economic shrinkage
in Hong Kong, she said, because the essential part of various
industries remains in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The government will do its utmost to create a favorable
environment for trade and industrial development, provide
personnel training and various kinds of software and hardware
facilities, and assist local business people explore the overseas
market, she said.
</P>
<P>
The government-funded Hong Kong Export Credit Insurance
Corporation, the Trade Development Council and the Productive
Council are working for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
On how to improve the competitiveness of the Hong Kong economy,
Yue said, it is important to attract and train a large number of
professionals, make an efficient use of funds and make full use of
land resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Leaders on Confronting Economic Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 21 (xinhua) -- Leaders of seven Western
industrialized countries committed to sustaining non-inflationary
economic growth in confronting global economic and financial
challenges.
</P>
<P>
In an economic statement issued here today by Group of Seven
(G-7) leaders who are attending the Denver Summit of the Eight,
they said that the increasing globalization of markets was an
important engine of world growth which provides both opportunities
and challenges to all countries.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to realize the full benefits of globalization for
all while meeting the challenges it presents," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that to reach this goal three major work must be
attended to:
</P>
<P>
--Implement policies to promote sustainable, non-inflationary
growth, create jobs, restore sound public finance and meet the
challenge of the aging population;
</P>
<P>
--Work together with other countries to promote open markets
for trade and investment and to support global financial stability;
</P>
<P>
--Promote the successful integration of the transition and
developing countries of all regions of the world into the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
The statement welcomed the efforts of European Union countries
to achieve a successful introduction of the well-functioning
European Monetary Unit, underpinned by sound macroeconomic and
structural policies.
</P>
<P>
The leader pledged to undertake structural reforms to address
"one of the most important challenge" to the West -- the economic,
financial and social implications of the changing demographics in
the aging society.
</P>
<P>
They approved the final report on promoting financial stability
presented by finance ministers. The leaders reiterated the
commitment to promoting international monetary stability and asked
finance ministers to continue to cooperate closely on economic
policy and in the exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the Western leaders reaffirmed
their commitment to widely-shared economic growth and development
and full partnership with developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"We attached high priority to full and effective implementation
of the Uruguay Round agreements to support the goals of further
trade liberization to spread the benefits of globalization," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also pledgeed debt relief for the poorest countries
and combating corruption and financial crimes.
</P>
<P>
The 3-day Denver Summit of the Eight, G-7 leaders and the
Russian president, will end on June 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
