<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handover-Related Press Commentary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22, (Xinhua) -- The following is the gist of an
article carried by Wen Wei Po today.
</P>
<P>
The article dwells on the wisdom of the "one country, two
systems" thinking advocated by the late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"'One country, two systems' is a new thinking in the history of
mankind. It was proposed neither by Britain, nor by any other
foreign country, but by China. Proposition of this great concept
was due primarily to Deng Xiaoping," the article says.
</P>
<P>
The article reviews comments on the "one country, two systems"
thinking made by Chinese Vice-Premier-cum-Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen at a recent Beijing seminar on the thinking.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen said, "Analyzed theoretically, the 'one country,
two systems' thinking has two characteristics: first, it is
sourced in an ideology characterized by 'emancipating the mind'
and 'seeking truth from facts;' and second, it is a thinking used
to achieve the reunification of China, a new method for resolving
contradictions through peaceful means."
</P>
<P>
The article says the Chinese government has always adopted a
"seeking truth from facts" stand and principle in dealing with the
Hong Kong question.
</P>
<P>
In October 1949, when it reached the northern bank of the
Shenzhen river separating Hong Kong from the rest of China, the
Chinese People's Liberation Army did not advance further south.
The leaders of the Chinese Communist Party maintained that, from
an overall point of view, it was not appropriate to resolve the
Hong Kong and Macao questions immediately. It is a strategic
decision of the Chinese government then to leave Hong Kong and
Macao as they were to serve a bridge and window whereby New China
could have contacts with the outside world, thereby breaking
Western encirclement of and embargo against China.
</P>
<P>
"Founders of New China, at the very beginning of dealing with
the Hong Kong question, adopted a line of thinking based on
'seeking truth from facts,'" the article says.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the 1970s, the Chinese government decided to
focus on three major tasks: modernization, national reunification
and the maintenance of world peace. This indicated that the time
to resolve the Hong Kong question was ripe.
</P>
<P>
In using the "one country, two systems' formula to settle the
Hong Kong question, the purpose is to recover Hong Kong on the one
hand and to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity and stability on the
other, the article says.
</P>
<P>
To do this, the solution should be acceptable to the three
sides involved: China, Hong Kong and Britain. Such a solution,
according to Deng Xiaoping, can only be a "one country, two
systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
"This strongly represents the principle of 'seeking truth from
facts,'" the article says.
</P>
<P>
The article goes on to say that it is great wisdom to use "one
country, two systems" to achieve national reunification because it
is a new method, a peaceful method, to "resolve contradictions."
</P>
<P>
"One country, two systems" means that the method of peaceful
coexistence can be used not only in the international arena, but
also within "one country" to resolve contradictions arising from
"two systems," the article says.
</P>
<P>
"The great wisdom of this lies in the fact that the method can
not only allow contradictions to coexist peacefully but also allow
otherwise contradictory things to be mutually complementary and
beneficial," the article says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
