<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closer Economic Links Between HK and Inland Areas Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The return of Hong Kong to China
on July 1 offers new opportunities for bilateral economic
development between the interior areas of China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Since China began implementing the policies of economic reform
and opening to the outside world in 1978, economic cooperation
between the two sides has strengthened on the basis of mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
In the 1979-1996 period, Hong Kong has established 162,000
projects in the interior areas, involving a combined direct
investment of 100 billion US dollars, which make up 56.2 percent
of total overseas investment in China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hong Kong has been one of the most important trading
partners of China's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
According customs statistics, the trade volume between the two
sides totaled 40.7 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral economic cooperation benefits both sides. On the one
hand, Hong Kong has provided funds, information and managerial
expertise for the interior areas, fueling economic development
there. On the other hand, the "China factor" has contributed
greatly to the economic success of Hong Kong. Thanks to the
interior areas' vast market, improved investment environment, rich
natural resources and cheap labor, Hong Kong has transferred most
of its manufacturing industry to the mainland. This has allowed
Hong Kong to change its product mix and shift to
technology-intensive industries and services.
</P>
<P>
Economists on both sides held that there will be more favorable
factors promoting bilateral economic cooperation on a bigger scale
after Hong Kong returns to the embrace of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The central government has decided to speed up economic
development in central and western parts of China in the country's
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) period.
</P>
<P>
The country is to invest an estimated 300 billion US dollars in
communications and infrastructure projects alone in these regions
in the next few years. Hong Kong is expected to play a key role in
raising funds for such projects.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict the following trends with regard to economic
cooperation between Hong Kong and the interior areas of China:
</P>
<P>
-- While continuing to invest in the Pearl River Delta and
other coastal areas, Hong Kong businesses are expected to expand
their presence in east, north and northwest China. The Pudong New
Area in Shanghai and the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
River will be prime areas of their future investment;
</P>
<P>
-- Hong Kong is expected to enhance cooperation with the five
Special Economic Zones, the Pudong New Area and the Suzhou
Industrial Park in developing high-tech and value-added products;
</P>
<P>
-- Hong Kong will take its advantage of being an international
financial center to raise funds for the technological
transformation of industrial enterprises in interior areas;
</P>
<P>
-- Investment from Hong Kong will continue to flow into the
fields of infrastructure and services;
</P>
<P>
-- Large financial consortia and listed companies in Hong Kong
are expected to be the mainstay of investment in interior areas;
and
</P>
<P>
-- The interior areas of China and Hong Kong will join hands in
 investing in other parts of the world and in expanding overseas
markets.  
</P>
