<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Cut Fail to Lure Car Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- There was no nationwide follow-up
buying spree after a major car maker cut its car prices a few
weeks ago, according to the "Business Weekly".
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Automotive Industry Corp (SAIC) cut Santana 2000 car
prices by 11,000 yuan. Now the most expensive Santana 2000 sedan
costs 182,000 yuan, while the cheapest costs 164,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Shanghai Volkswagen Co, a Sino-German joint venture,
produced about 250,000 cars, including 110,000 Santana 2000s. The
ordinary model cost about 100,000 yuan, but Santana 2000s cost
175,000 yuan to 198,800 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The price gap between the ordinary Santana and the new Santana
2000 is unreasonably wide," said Wang Runzhi, a State Planning
Commission official. This is the main reason we approved their
applications to cut prices," she said.
</P>
<P>
Industrial analysts said SAIC had to compare the price of Jetta
models produced by its sister company, a Changchun-based joint
venture of Volkswagen and First Automotive Works. The Jetta cost
about 143,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Chang Qiche, an expert in Beijing, as saying
that the Santana 2000 sedans could have fallen lower if the
company had not considered the interests of its Changchun
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoyu, director of the automotive department under the
Ministry of Machine Building Industry, said that the price cut
range for the automobile industry would be as much as 10 per cent
to survive the oversupply in the auto sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
