<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Industry Sales Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' industry sales in
the first quarter of the year went up by five percent to 104
billion pesos (4 billion U.S. dollars) from a year ago, according
to the latest figures released by the Trade and Industry
Department.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance of the pulp and paper, automotive and
sugar subsectors which registered a decline of as much as 57
percent eroded gains from growth sectors, the figures showed.
</P>
<P>
But double digit growth in the cement and electronics as well
as engineering and metalworking subsectors somewhat offset the
declines.
</P>
<P>
The sugar sector, still suffering from over importation, was
the biggest loser with its sales volume plunging 50 percent and
value down 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
Another loser, the textile sector registered a 26-percent
decline in sales volume and a 17-percent drop in value due to the
low demand for finishing mills.
</P>
<P>
The gainers, in terms of both volume and value, were led by the
cement manufacturing sector which expanded 24 percent in output
and 28 percent in value owing to a boom in construction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
