<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Cuts Financial Expenditure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic is cutting its
financial expenditure due to a financial deficit of 12 billion
coruny (about 400 million U.S. dollars) first seen in several
years.
</P>
<P>
The country's revenue stood at 191 billion coruny (about 6.3
billion U.S. dollars) for the first five months of this year while
its spendings reached 202 billion coruny (some 6.8 billion
U.S. dollars), said Ludmila Nutilova, spokeswoman of the Finance
Ministry here today.
</P>
<P>
Starting from April, the Czech government began its austerity
measures to curb the increasing deficit by cutting its spendings
by 7.56 percent, dismissing civil servants, postponing the
construction of public buildings and cancelling routine state
banquets.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts attribute the deficit to the nation's slowed
down economic growth, unfavorable foreign trade, loss-making
enterprises that count for one third of all enterprises and a weak
coruny since beginning of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
