<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "El Nino" Climate Phenomenon Threatens Animals in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The "El Nino" climate phenomenon has
threatened the life of unique animals living in the Galapagos
Islands archipelago, Ecuador's biggest tourist asset and one of
the last wildlife sanctuaries in the world.
</P>
<P>
The sea water temperature around the islands has reached 28
degrees centigrade that greatly increased risks for animals, such
as sea lions, penguins and albatrosses, by chasing away their
foods including fish and other species.
</P>
<P>
Scientists on the spot warned the water temperature was three or
four degrees above the normal and could go up to 30 to cause the
extermination of many animals existing in the volcanic
archipelago, such as giant turtles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970622.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Host Asia-Pacific Higher Education Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from 28 countries and
regions will meet here Monday to discuss challenges and
requirements to higher education and human resources development
in the Asia-Pacific region and beyond in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos, who is now on a visit to the
Middle East, will address the meeting -- the World Congress on
Higher Education and Human Resources Development in the
Asia-Pacific -- after his return on June 25.
</P>
<P>
This meeting is one of the two to be held in Asia in the run-up
to the World Congress on Higher Education organized by the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) to be
held in Paris next year, today's newspaper reports quoted Higher
Education Commissioner Mona Valisno as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the expected attending countries and regions are Brunei,
Cambodia, China, Egypt, Germany, South Africa and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, the participants will exchange
views on financing of the region's higher education, borderless
learning environments in higher education in the region and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will provide valuable inputs to the
UNESCO-sponsored regional and world congress in Tokyo in late
1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
