<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Beijing Meteorological Satellite Ground Station received
a highly visible cloud picture from a newly-launched
meteorological satellite at 13:30 Beijing time yesterday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first cloud chart sent back to the earth by Fengyun
2, a meteorological satellite launched on June 10 and successfully
stationed over the equator at 105 degrees east longitude a week
later.
</P>
<P>
-- Leaders of China's non-Communist parties and the All-China
Federation of Industry and Commerce held a forum at the Great Hall
of the People yesterday to greet Hong Kong's upcoming return to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The Memorial Hall of Li Xiannian, the third president of the
People's Republic of China, opened yesterday in Li's hometown,
Hong'an County, in central China's Hubei Province, to mark the
fifth anniversary of his death.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun stressed during a recent
inspection tour in northwest China that the area must conserve
water and soil resources and improve agricultural production
conditions.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Great Wall Industrial Corporation (CGWIC) and the
US-based Hughes Space and Communications Company struck a
long-term deal yesterday in Beijing, under which the Chinese
aerospace company will launch 10 satellites for Hughes from late
1998 through the end of 2006.
</P>
<P>
"Business Weekly of China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- As exports grew rapidly in the past five months, a senior
economist in Beijing called for awareness of imports, which have
been falling since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
-- While American carmakers are shutting down auto plants to
improve productivity and increase profits, some Chinese carmakers
are cutting prices to capture a bigger market share.
</P>
<P>
