<HEADLINE> China's Largest Water Diversion Works to Become Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- After three years of construction,
China's largest water diversion works is expected to be put to
full-scale operation in early July in Dalian, a coastal city in
northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, drawing water from Biliu River 150 kilometers
outside Dalian, is to provide 1.2 million tons of water daily to
the city, said an official in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
The city government financed the project with more than three
million yuan (362 million US dollars), of which 1.4 billion yuan
(168 million dollars) is in loans from the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Dalian is one of the Chinese cities that suffers from an
extreme water shortage.
</P>
<P>
The official said the diversion project will help to attract
foreign investment, in addition to improving conditions of the
city's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the water problem will not be an obstacle to
the city's economic development in the coming eight years. Dalian
now has a total of 6,000 foreign-funded ventures.
</P>
<P>
The city has moved out more than 40 factories from the urban
areas to ease the water-supply pressures, and will move another 60
factories.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city is making preparations to draw water from
other rivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
