<HEADLINE> Philippines' Unemployment Rate Drops to 10.4 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' unemployment rate
dropped to 10.4 percent in April to 3.3 million people from 10.9
percent recorded in the same period of last year, according to the
latest labor force survey by the National Statistics Office.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey said, the double-digit unemployment rate in
April is significantly higher than the 7.7 percent registered
during the January survey.
</P>
<P>
The National Statistics Office, which conducts four rounds of
survey on labor force every year, explained that the April survey
usually registers the highest unemployment figure due to the
entrance of new graduates in the job market.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year of 1997, the government has set an ambitious
target of 7 percent unemployment rate, from the 9.8 percent
recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
The office said that the April survey reflected a national
employment rate of 89.6 percent, slightly higher than the 89.1
percent registered a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"The estimated national labor force population in April 1997
reached 31.4 million persons. Last year's comparative estimate was
30.7 million persons," it said.
</P>
<P>
The labor force survey said that many of the jobs were
generated in the services and agricultural sectors, with a total
share of 41.8 percent and 41.3 percent respectively, and the
industry sector got a share of 16.9 percent of the total
employment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
