<HEADLINE> Christie Runs Fastest in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Linford Christie of Britain recorded
his 16th victory in the European Cup by clocking the fastest time
of the year in Europe in Munich on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Olympic champion in 1992, sprinted ahead to win
the 100 meters in 10.04 seconds, equalling his record of the meet
set last year in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Geir Moen of Norway was second in 10.18, and Andrey Fedoriv of
Russia finished third in a personal best of 10.19.
</P>
<P>
Christie has now won the European Cup 100 meters on eight
consecutive seasons, and he will contest the 200 meters on Sunday
to try to add to his impressive record.
</P>
<P>
Spain became the surprise leaders in the men's competition
after the first day as Fermin Cacho won the 1,500 meters and
Arturo Ortiz took the high jump title.
</P>
<P>
Russia also scored 52 points but ranked second as Kiril Sosunov
became its sole winner in the long jump final.
</P>
<P>
The host Germany was third just with one point behind.
</P>
<P>
Cacho unleashed a devastating burst of speed 40 meters from the
line to win in three minutes 37.79 seconds, beating Italy's
Gennaro Di Napoli to second in 3:37.81.
</P>
<P>
German Heinz Weis won the hammer with 81.42 metres, the third
best throw of the year, and Dieter Baumann, the 1992 Olympic 5,000
meters champion, won in a new championship record of 7:41.08.
</P>
<P>
The women's competition was lead by Russia with 67 points with
Germany second on 63 and Ukraine a distant third on 49.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Inna Lasovskaya, a silver medallist in Atlanta, won
the women's triple jump in a European Cup best of 14.91 meters,
the third best leap of the year.
</P>
<P>
Gabriela Szabo of Romania set her 5,000 meters Cup best of
15:02.68, and Roberta Brunet of Italy finished second in 15:02.87,
also inside the previous best.
</P>
<P>
Anzelha Balakhonova of Ukraine cleared 4.25 meters to win the
pole vault, the first time the event has been included in the
women's competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
