<HEADLINE> Eight Powers Call for Protection of Peace in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Group of
Seven industrialized nations and Russia today called on the Balkan
leaders to protect peace in Bosnia and would face a cut-off of aid
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
A draft statement, which is to be approved by the leaders of the
U.S., Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Canada, Russia and the
European Union, urged the implementation of the civil aspects of the
Dayton peace accords signed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
It criticized Croatia and Serbia for failing to demonstrate
stronger commitment to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to continue to help the states of this region,
but our continued commitment is not unconditional," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was firmly determined to pull all its 8,500 troops out
of Bosnia by June 1998. But the Europeans are reluctant, fearing
that bloodshed may reoccur in the region.
</P>
<P>
European leaders at the Denver summit have expressed their concern
to U.S. President Bill Clinton about the U.S. decision to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton refused to budge. "As the president has
indicated, there is a defined mission that expires June of 1998 and
that's the timetable we're on," said White House spokesman Michael
McCurry today.
</P>
<P>
The draft statement sidestepped whether the peacekeeping force in
Bosnia will be pulled out as scheduled next year.
</P>
<P>
"We support the mission of the stabilization force to help provide
a secure environment by June 1998," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
