<HEADLINE> Pakistan FM Wants to Devise Mechanism for Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub has hoped the foreign secretaries of Pakistan and India would
in their on-going round of talks devise a mechanism for a
sustained, integrated and structured dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Gohar expressed the hope here on Saturday when he met with
Indian Foreign Secretary Salman Haider, who leads a six-member
Indian delegation in the current talks which began on Friday.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating the Pakistan's commitment to improve
relations with India, Gohar emphasized the need to avoid any
action which could mar the atmosphere of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Haider said that they were approaching the foreign secretaries'
level talks in a positive manner.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the useful exchanges he had with his Pakistani
counterpart, the Indian foreign secretary said that the two sides
were engaged in thorough exercise to devise a mechanism for the
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Haider also called on Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
"The progress should be uniform on a broad spectrum of
Indo-Pakistan issues including the core issue of Kashmir," Sharif
said. "There should be meaningful progress in the talks."
</P>
<P>
Haider said that Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral had
instructed him to assure Sharif that India "wanted to open a new
chapter in the relations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The present talks are scheduled to conclude on Monday. It is
the second time that India and Pakistan are holding such kind of
talks since March this year after a suspension of over three
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
