<HEADLINE> World Powers Committed to Meet Global Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DENVER, Colorado, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven
industrialized countries and Russia today pledged to meet together
the global challenges ranging from illicit nuclear trafficking to
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a report to their leaders after a meeting on political
issues, foreign ministers of the eight countries said that their
countries are "committed to a strategy of global integration aimed
at fostering international peace and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
The global challenges include non-proliferation of nuclear
weapons, anti-personnel landmines, trans-national organized
crimes, counterterrorism and the United Nations reform.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference following the meeting, U.S.
Secretary Madeleine Albright indicated that the challenges needs
the efforts of every country, stressing that no one nation can
resolve the issues alone.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers said that they would undertake more
enhanced information-sharing and cooperation among law
enforcement, intelligence, and custom services in the fight
against illicit nuclear trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. would organize the first meeting on fighting nuclear
material smuggling in November 1997 in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers said in the report that their countries
would strengthen cooperation to combat and eliminate terrorism and
called on all countries to join the international conventions on
terrorism in order to eliminate international terrorism by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to develop system to fight against high-tech
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministers also discussed situations in
Democratic Republic of the Congo, Republic of Congo (Brazzaville),
Haiti and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"All Afghan parties and concerned countries should abide by the
provisions of recent resolutions on Afghanistan adopted by the
U.N. Security Council and General Assembly," they declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
