<HEADLINE> Car Bomb Rocks Center of Belfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A car bomb rocked the center of
Belfast today, which is thought to have been aimed at two senior
republicants who were in the vehicle, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate claim of responsibility but pro-British
Loyalists seeking to avenge the Irish Republic Army (IRA) which
killed two police on Monday were under suspicion, security sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Three people were slightly injured in the bombing. They were
taken to hospital but were later released.
</P>
<P>
The explosion took place in the tense run-up to the annual
Protestant marching season and amid British impatience at the
failure of the IRA to call a truce to get its political wing, Sinn
Fein.
</P>
<P>
Security officials believe that Loyalist terrorists may be
behind the attack.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair voiced anger at the IRA
killing of two police in Lurgan last Monday shortly after his
officials renewed contact with Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
Blair is expected to spell out his newly-elected government's
position in Northern Ireland in a major statement to parliament on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
